a senior commander ordered his officers sunday to view film footage of troops brutally beating arab prisoners and said the israeli army must not become ``a rabble army.''
maj. gen. amram mitzna, head of the central command that is in charge of the occupied west bank of the jordan river, gathered all officers over the rank of platoon commander sunday and showed them the footage shot by cbs news in the west bank town of nablus, israel radio reported
i'm against those who think we can sweep internal problems under the carpet just because they're not pretty,'' mitzna said earlier on israel radio. ``we have to make sure we don't become a rabble army.''
the film, which showed four soldiers in nablus kicking and beating two palestinians last thursday, shocked many israelis who believed violence by soldiers during three months of palestinian demonstrations had receded after new army orders last week limited the use of force
some members of prime minister yitzhak shamir's right-wing likud bloc defended the soldiers
i'm against the lynch atmosphere,'' said likud legislator pinchas goldstein. ``there was no need to arrest the soldiers.''
transport minister chaim korfu, also of likud, told the cabinet sunday the press should be barred from the occupied lands for three months
we are in a confrontation,'' korfu later told israel army radio. ``we must take these minimal measures when we know for certain (the media) is responsible for some of the violence.''
according to u.n. figures, 74 arabs have been killed by the israelis during the violent in the occupied west bank and gaza strip since dec. 10. hundreds have been wounded and there have been many cases of soldiers severely beating palestinians
the cbs film showed four soldiers, members of a tank unit, kicking the palestinians whose hands were tied behind their backs and smashing them on the legs and arms with fist-sized rocks
the four were arrested and their deputy unit commander, a captain, was suspended. it was announced saturday that the four soldiers would be tried by a military court. mitzna ordered the release of the two arabs
amalia harpaz, the mother of one of the four soldiers filmed by cbs, said her son saguy had changed since he began serving in the occupied territories 10 weeks ago
i educated my son to go the army, take responsibility and defend the country,'' she told israel radio. ``what has happened is that he has turned into a beater of women and children.''
she is a resident of kibbutz gesher, a communal settlement
israel radio said several lawyers have offered to represent the soldiers without charge. it reported the lawyers said if anyone was responsible for a crime, it is israel's leaders. increased estimate on surface oil spill, updated figure on amount of this spill cleaned up. picks up 7th graf pvs, `western washington ...'</note>
a salvage crew raised a sunken oil barge sunday from the murky depths of guemes channel, one month after it sank and spilled some 70,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil into washington's inland waters
with the inverted barge held at the surface by thick cables strung from two giant cranes, crews began pumping the more than 300,000 gallons of oil that remained in the vessel into a second barge. officials said they wanted to get the stricken barge floating on its own before they attempted to slowly roll it right side up
a helicopter hovered overhead to track the movement of an oil sheen that appeared as the barge was raised. the sheen was caused by 500 to 1,000 gallons of lighter oil that was detected after the barge broke the surface about 7 a.m., said mark stewart of the state division of emergency management
the barge initially held about 22,000 gallons of light oil in addition to the heavy oil
stewart said surface skimmer boats had cleaned up about 160 gallons, while absorbent pads collected an additional, undetermined amount
the oil sheen moved about two miles south. coast guard lt. eldo delong said the sheen reached some kelp beds near burrows bay, but did not touch any beaches
state department of ecology workers said three seabirds were contaminated, but they did not appear badly injured and were not captured for cleaning
marine biologists and state environmental experts were assessing the damage from the bunker oil spill, which had been difficult to determine because the heavier-than-water oil had sunk
but ats kiuchi, a doe spokesman, said it appeared the fragile, inner coastal environment had avoided a disaster that, if the barge had spilled its entire cargo, would have been the worst oil spill in the state's history
western washington university's shannon point marine laboratory has found some oil in sea cucumbers, said paul cassidy, the lab's director of operations
the u.s. coast guard tug ``spike'' used absorbent pads to clean up some oil after the barge was raised while a second boat was positioned near shannon point, 100 yards away, to prevent any oil from reaching shore
the 176-foot-long barge, operated by olympic tug and barge of seattle, sank jan. 31 in about 130 feet of water four miles west of anacortes and about 100 yards off shannon point
the barge had been loaded at an oil refinery at anacortes and was being towed by a tug to seattle when it began listing and capsized
the cause of the sinking remained undetermined
coast guard lt. eldo delong said the barge will be taken to the anacortes city dock where a boom would be put around it and any remaining holes would be patched. eventually it will be taken to seattle, he said
a london newspaper said sunday that the united states has sent a secret envoy to iran to discuss re-establishing diplomatic links
the observer, in an unattributed story, did not identify the official but said he is apparently a close friend of president reagan and went to tehran two weeks ago. it said the envoy was traveling under the name of clark
the observer said the envoy met middle-ranking iranian officials, who asked for assurances that any arms embargo against them as proposed by the united nations should be delayed until early this summer
the united states is seeking a u.n. ban on arms sales because iran has not accepted a cease-fire agreement in its eight-year war with iraq
there have been no diplomatic relations since the u.s. embassy in tehran was stormed nov. 4, 1979, and held for 444 days with diplomats and others kept hostage inside
leaping luggage and sniffing out sneaky smugglers, the latest addition to miami international airport's k-9 corps has racked up impressive credits in his first two months on the beat, his human colleagues say
king, a romping 2-year-old cross between a black labrador retriever and a german short-haired pointer, has a nose that makes news
since the u.s. customs service gave king to metro-dade police, he has sniffed out $86,000 in drug-scented cash, 347 pounds of cocaine and helped collar four suspects, said police lt. larry martin
the beloved rookie, one of three canines used by metro-dade police at the airport, has all but matched the 400-pound career total of ringo, who just retired after about a decade, martin said
he's an up-and-coming dog,'' martin said of the enthusiastic pooch, who with handler detective ken buzzi, graduated from the u.s. customs dog training school in front royal, va
king and buzzi were still getting used to the domestic flight areas of miami international after their december graduation when they made their first score dec. 17
a man carrying christmas presents on a flight from denver fit the profile of a smuggler. denver police had been suspicious
the man agreed to a search and king ``alerted'' to a drug odor in his packages. more than $40,000 in drug-tainted cash was discovered, buzzi said
the fact that a specially trained dog identified the money as having been associated with narcotics was probable cause to seize it, buzzi said
soon afterward, king found a similar amount of drug-tainted cash packed in a mercedes benz
the two occupants of the car were arrested and are awaiting trial in dade county circuit court, buzzi said
king's abilities also led to the discovery of 185 pounds of cocaine and the arrest of two eastern airlines employees on feb. 1
the next day, he sniffed out 155 pounds of cocaine concealed underneath the floor in the belly of an l-1011 aircraft. he detected 7 pounds of cocaine on an earlier search to bring his total to 347 pounds, martin said
i worked mostly narcotics for the last 16 years,'' said buzzi. ``the biggest seizure i made was 600 pounds and it took me almost 10 years. but working with a detector dog, we've found almost 400 pounds in the first two months we were back from school
we're both still a green team. i've been a police officer for 18 years but i feel like a rookie again. it's like a whole new career,'' he said
while king has a ``super-fine nose,'' he is not perfect, buzzi said
king gets tired sometimes while working his eight-hour shift, ``but so far he's been on the money,'' he said
detector dogs cannot sniff the enormous volume of luggage, freight and planes used to smuggle narcotics and money through this primary port of entry for drugs, buzzi said
any dog and its handler are only as good as the watchful authorities who suggest likely targets
it was mostly luck and being in the right place at the right time,'' buzzi said
mohammed ali abu leban, accused of hurling a firebomb at israeli soldiers, saw his lawyer for the first time five minutes before he appeared in military court
the 19-year-old signed a confession written in hebrew, a language he does not know, and said interrogators abused him
as authorities round up growing numbers of arab suspects in an effort to quell nearly three months of unrest, israel's methods of detaining and trying palestinians has drawn a hail of criticism
i feel totally helpless in this sham of a system,'' said abu leban's attorney, jonathan kuttab, a palestinian who graduated from the university of virginia law school in charlottesville
in 98 percent of the cases, lawyers cannot see palestinian clients until after they `confess,' and judges will accept the `confession' at face value, no matter what you say,'' kuttab told the associated press
abu leban, shackled and dressed in a blue-jeans jacket, flashed a v-for-victory sign as he entered the tiny courtroom in a closed army base. he waved to his father, whom he was seeing for the first time since his arrest
abu leban had been held incommunicado for 18 days, until he signed a four-page confession. he said he signed only after interrogators beat him, deprived him of sleep and forced him to squat in a corner for hours
kuttab said it was unlikely his client's contentions would be accepted in court. allegations of unfairness in the military court system prompted the attorneys' association in the gaza strip to decide to boycott all military court proceedings
but israeli officials argue the system is fair
there are some exceptions. but a defendant who feels he was mistreated during interrogation can raise the issue in court, where due process of law is ensured,'' army prosecutor amos giora, a native of ann arbor, mich., said in an interview
giora and other israelis argue the only obvious shortcoming in the military court system was redressed by defense minister yitzhak rabin earlier this month when he announced that israel, after 20 years of occupation, would establish army appeal courts
kuttab said figures assembled by palestinian lawyers show the total number of arab detainees, normally about 3,000 at any one time, has doubled and the army has set up four new prisons with tent barracks in the occupied west bank and gaza
according to the army, 1,927 palestinians were arrested and 93 placed in jail for six months without trial under emergency regulations from dec. 8 to feb. 9. the arab-owned palestine press service puts the number of arabs jailed without trial at 147
the process from arrest to trial in the military court system is well documented. a palestinian suspected of participating in anti-israeli activities is usually detained in the middle of the night because soldiers fear their presence in arab towns or refugee camps during the day might spark protests
the detainee is handcuffed, often blindfolded, and taken to a military prison. no arrest warrant is ever shown and family members are not told where the suspect is being taken
it often takes a lawyer several weeks to track down his new client, who can be held incommunicado for up to six months. a judge is required to order a detention extension after the first 18 days
during the period of interrogation, the detainee is routinely subjected to beatings, forced to spend long hours in uncomfortable positions, threatened and submitted to other psychological measures,'' kuttab said
usually before the first 18-day period is up, the defendant breaks down and confesses to a variety of illegal activities,'' kuttab said. ``only after this is he permitted to see an attorney, and only then is the attorney told what charges his client faces.''
abu leban entered court with five other arab defendants, four of whom had no attorney present. kuttab was able to see his client and the charge sheet against him only minutes before the court session began
kuttab argued in court that abu leban signed the confession only after being abused. he asked for, and was granted, a separate hearing about the admissiblity of the evidence
kuttab said he did not intend actually to present a case on whether the evidence should be admitted, but only to use the extra time to try to plea bargain a shorter sentence
if i protest, his interrogator will deny it and he will just end up getting a tougher sentence,'' kuttab said
what hurts most about the process is the pretense of propriety,'' he said. ``with a judge and a prosecutor and a defense attorney, it looks all right from the outside. but in fact, on a certain level, i feel i am a collaborator in the evil system.''
at least i brought him some cigarettes,'' kuttab said of abu leban, shaking his head as he left court. ``i've turned into a social worker more than a lawyer in this system.'' project</head>
the fertile missouri river bottom lands where the arikara, hidatsa and mandan indians thrived for seven centuries are gone forever, buried beneath the waters of lake sakakawea
the 200-mile-long reservoir drove the indians onto higher, less productive land, sliced their reservation into isolated sections and is blamed for precipitating soaring unemployment and alcoholism
the three tribes, who say they were coerced into surrendering the bottom lands without just compensation as the lake filled behind garrison dam, believe they have a chance this year to get $178.4 million that they and a special federal commission think they deserve
the problem has been with us for 40 years. the time is right for a resolution,'' said tribal chairman edward lone fight
the tribes, which total about 7,700 people, are asking the state's congressional delegation to introduce legislation that would give them $3.6 million a year for 50 years plus 4 percent interest on the unpaid balance of the settlement
the money would come from federal hydropower revenues, rather than the u.s. treasury, which tribal leaders believe should make the legislation more palatable to congress
the bill also would fund municipal water projects on the reservation and authorize, but not pay for, replacement of a hospital and other facilities destroyed by the reservoir
lone fight says the bill ``is something that's supportable'' in congress
but the federal bureau of indian affairs opposes further compensation for the tribes. rural electric cooperatives don't like the idea of dipping into hydropower revenues. and members of the state's congressional delegation have yet to support the bill
we hope that something can be introduced this session. but until we can find something that everyone feels comfortable with, nothing can be introduced,'' said mary jo vrem, an aide to the senate select committee on indian affairs
the tribes accepted $12.6 million from congress in 1950, but garrison dam was already built and lake sakakawea was forming when the money was offered. the tribes and their supporters say the indians had no choice but to take the settlement
when the indian people were negotiating for the best possible deal, the water was up to their ankles ... and the offers were going down,'' lone fight said
when dam construction began in the 1940s, 90 percent of the indians lived and farmed in the river valley, as their ancestors had for seven centuries. unemployment on the reservation was negligible
today, unemployment exceeds 50 percent and alcoholism is rampant, problems that have been linked to the disruption caused by garrison dam. about 3,400 indians live on the reservation; another 4,300 tribal members live elsewhere
lake sakakawea is named for a shoshone guide who worked for the lewis and clark expedition up the missouri river in 1804
in my 66 years, i have seen a drastic change from being self-sufficent to being a very desperate economic situation,'' said luther grinnell, a tribal judge. grinnell grew up on a family farm near elbowoods, the reservation's main town before it was inundated
the tribes grew their own vegetables and cattle, cut firewood from trees along the river and mined nearby coal deposits, grinnell said
we never heard of unemployment because everyone had their farms, and those who had jobs didn't farm,'' grinnell said
a five-member panel appointed by interior secretary donald hodel concluded in 1986 that the tribes were owed $178 million to $412 million in compensation
the joint tribal advisory committee agreed with indian claims that the lake destroyed their self-sufficient way of life and precipitated the tribes' continuing social problems
if the tribes get the settlement, the money would be earmarked for programs, such as work projects and alcohol treatment, that would attack the reservation's social ills, lone fight said
however, in a recent meeting with tribal leaders, assistant secretary for indian affairs ross swimmer claimed that the tribes have been adequately compensated through the federal services they receive
swimmer's position was characterized by ray cross, an attorney for the tribes, as ``disingenuous.''
bureau of indian affairs officials will meet soon with members of north dakota's congressional delegation to discuss the tribes' proposal, bia spokesman carl shaw said. democratic totals include ``super delegates'' in addition to results from iowa, new hampshire and maine.</note>
