enrollment is up and the debt is down at fisk university, where only a few years ago students shivered in unheated dormitories because the historically black private institution could not pay its gas bill
as fisk winds down its celebration of black history month, which included the dedication of a stamp honoring author james weldon johnson, faculty and students also celebrated the university's return from the brink of financial disaster
when the nashville gas co. cut off service in early 1984 until fisk paid a $170,000 debt, students brought space heaters to class and joined with faculty and staff members to raise funds to ensure the university's survival. the overall debt mounted to $4.1 million, but classes continued
henry ponder, appointed fisk's president in july 1984, led the school on a course of austerity programs and aggressive fund-raising
when ponder was told, for example, that boiler repairs would cost $350,000, he found a fisk alumnus, a maintenance expert, who did it for only $60,000
ponder acknowledged in a recent interview that things are better at fisk, but added ``you have to get the public to understand that help is still needed to get the resources to move this institution ... to the forefront of educational institutions in this country
i don't say that lightly. that's where we've been and we will get back,'' said ponder, who said the school did not lower its academic standards during its financial troubles
today, debt at fisk has been reduced to $200,000 and its endowment has reached $3.9 million. an unrestricted gift of $1.3 million by entertainer bill cosby in december 1986 gave the school a boost, but officials say they have received substantial grass-roots support, too
however, three of the university's 23 trustees announced friday that they will resign at the end of the school year. one trustee said the resignations were related to the accountability of those charged with day-to-day administration. fisk's financial aid director and assistant director were fired in december for allegedly failing to fill out forms to receive financial aid
faculty salaries have increased 30 percent over the last three years to an average of $32,000 for a tenured professor, although still below the $35,000 to $40,000 ponder said is appropriate
aggressive recruiting of students brought enrollment, which dipped to 500 at one point, up to 644 students in the 1988 spring semester, an increase of 27 percent over the 1987 spring semester, said harrison deshields, director of the office of admissions and records
bryon cobb, a student from huntsville, texas, said fisk's role in black history in america was important to him
fisk introduced the black spiritual to the world, it was active in the civil rights movement, w.e.b. dubois went to college here,'' cobb said
in addition, he said, ``my understanding is that a degree from fisk is as respected as one from harvard.''
the financial crisis at the school had some positive benefits for the fisk community, said roland hayes robinson, now a graduate student
the student body handled the crisis well, we shared space heaters. it united us. we were able to confront a problem and come through it,'' robinson sid
the university, founded in 1867 by the freedmen's bureau during reconstruction, is no stranger to struggle. in fact, the campus was purchased with $150,000 raised by the college's jubilee singers during a european tour in the 1870s
the earnings of the singers, whose tours still bring $60,000 a year to fisk, also paid for building jubilee hall, whose exterior was recently restored with a $150,000 federal grant
james weldon johnson, a poet who was a diplomat and an early organizer of the national association for the advancement of colored people, was a professor at fisk in the early 1930s. w.e.b. dubois, a philosopher and writer who graduated from fisk in 1888, also helped found the naacp and was the first black to earn a doctorate from harvard
i think students are attracted here because it has the reputation of a good community. when they get here, they find out we have a dynamic science faculty and many of our students go to medical and dental schools,'' ponder said. about 60 percent of fisk graduates enroll for postgraduate study
revais mitchell, executive assistant to the president and a history professor, said fisk's financial problems mirrored those of other liberal arts college, but were worse
in the 1960s and 1970s the philosophy of supporting a liberal arts education dried up and the interest shifted to business degrees,'' mitchell said
but mitchell said the quality of education at fisk has never suffered and that peeling paint and cold classrooms don't mean poor academics
i try to tell my students that there has always been an element of suffering in the tradition of black education,'' he said
thousands of students marched through london saturday, waving banners, chanting and banging drums to protest the government's proposed education reform bill
police, who closed several main roads to traffic, estimated about 10,000 demonstrators participated but the nationl union of students put the figure at 15,000-20,000
at one point, some 200 students sat down for several minutes at the entrance to 10 downing street, official residence of prime minister margaret thatcher. police said there were no arrests during the demonstration
student leaders say education secretary kenneth baker's measure will result in less student representation on college governing bodies and give industrial and commercial organizations too much influence in higher education and education for adults. baker claims his bill will raise standards and improve the quality of state education
the bill is now before parliament
three mexican nationals, including a former mexican police detective charged in the torture-murder of a u.s. drug agent, were convicted of conspiring to murder a u.s. customs agent
the charges grew out of a series of meetings with an undercover investigator in which defendant raul lopez alvarez offered to murder the customs agent for a $25,000 fee. no killing took place
lopez, 29, who also faces charges in the 1985 slaying of u.s. drug enforcement administration agent enrique camarena, was convicted friday of conspiracy to murder a federal agent and conspiracy to kidnap a federal agent
two men lopez hired in mexico to assist him, carlos quintero maldonado, 25, and fabian jimenez martinez, 22, also were convicted in the conspiracy. quintero was acquitted on a charge that he traveled to the united states from mexico to carry out the murder plot
the men could receive life imprisonment. sentencing was scheduled for april 18 before u.s. district judge pamela m. rymer
lawyers for the defendants had argued that lopez and the two men he hired never intended to carry out the murder, but had planned all along to stage a ``rip-off'' of the undercover drug agent with whom they were negotiating. they believed that the undercover agent was a narcotics dealer
lopez, a former homicide investigator for the mexican state judicial police, told undercover agents he was an ``enforcer'' for the powerful narcotics organization of rafael caro quintero and ernesto fonseca carrillo and had a direct role in camarena's abduction and torture
in 12 hours of government tapes presented as evidence, lopez bragged about his knowledge of camarena's torture and promised to repeat it on the customs agent
if it was part of a scam, they oversold it too much,'' said jury foreman david armas, 28, a postal worker from alhambra. ``especially when they talked about killing someone _ you looked at their faces, and they showed no remorse.''
nine people have been indicted in the camarena case, two of whom will be tried with lopez. caro and fonseca are jailed in mexico city in connection with the case. lopez had been charged in mexico with the camarena murder, but was later released. real name determined, picking up 6th graf pvs, `i'm shocked...'. subs penultimate graf, `if convicted...', to give suspect's real name.</note>
a man accused of attempting to sexually assault actress tracy scoggins, a co-host of the miss usa pageant here, was rearrested saturday after a judge's decision to set him free on $100 bond sparked protests
he later was freed again after posting a much higher bond
the man, pedro concepcion padilla, 35, of el paso, was initially arrested thursday night after the assault in a hotel elevator. he was released early friday on $100 bond set by associate municipal magistrate rodolfo romero. but the low bond infuriated state district judge brunson moore, as well as miss scoggins, and moore ordered him arrested again
padilla turned himself in at 9:35 a.m. saturday and jailed again on $100,000 bond. he posted the required 15 percent of that amount later in the day and was freed after spending about five hours in custody
officials said the man originally gave authorities a false name, antonio garcia
he was re-arrested through the help of his attorney, according to sheriff's capt. paco aguirre
i'm shocked and i'm outraged,'' miss scoggins said friday after the suspect's release. ``what this says to me is that a man like this can save himself a whole expensive night of dinner and dancing and just pay $100 to assault the woman of his choice. that's a pretty good deal.''
miss scoggins, who starred in the abc television series ``the colbys,'' suffered minor bruises during the attack. security guards and other guests who heard her screams came to her aid and subdued the attacker, she said
if convicted, padilla could be sentenced to up to 10 years in prison and fined up to $5,000
miss scoggins, who lives in malibu, calif., is in el paso to be co-host of the miss usa pageant, which will be broadcast live tuesday nationwide. bgng, `president reagan' to update with oas debate, playing of tape of mrs. delvalle; picks up 9th graf pvs bgng, `chewning said questions'</note>
reagan administration officials said saturday that eric arturo delvalle, recognized by the united states as panama's president, decided on his own to go into hiding, but that he remained in telephone contact with u.s. diplomats in panama city
delvalle is ``safe and in high spirits'' after escaping arrest, and the struggle against the country's military leader will continue, delvalle's envoy to washington said
the permanent council of the organization of american states, after a lengthy and at times heated debate saturday night on the situation in panama, took no position on the turmoil there
reagan administration officials denied participating in delvalle's escape, though they said the u.s. ambassador to panama, arthur h. davis, was in contact with delvalle by telephone
they said they were not sure what delvalle's next move would be
president reagan, who usually spends weekends at camp david, md., was at the white house receiving reports on the fast-moving situation
the 30-member oas council sidestepped a decision on whether to seat as panama's ambassador to the organization robert leyton, the current envoy who is loyal to panamanian military chief manuel antonio noriega, or larence chewning fabrega, delvalle's delegate. there had been indications from officials of the american delegation that the council would seat neither man, chosing instead to recognize soraya cano, a panamanian career diplomat who is a member of the panamanian delegation to the oas
the start of the formal council debate had been delayed for five hours while the envoys wrangled in private over the question of whom to credential as panama's representative
but when the debate commenced, shortly after 9 p.m. est, no resolutions were offered dealing with that sticky question. instead, leyton was admitted to take part in the debate, at least for the time being, and he launched into a tirade against the united states, accusing it of trying to destabilize his government
i wish to somehow resolve the crisis in the government of panama,'' leyton said. ``but this is not the forum.''
leyton steadfastly denied u.s. charges that noriega has been involved in drug trafficking, although the former panamanian ambassador to the united states, gabriel lewis, told the council, ``we are suffering a new phenomenon _ narco-militarism. this narcotic militarism knows no frontier.''
richard t. mccormack, the u.s. ambassador to the oas, said the united states could not accept the decision by the panamanian national assembly in which delvalle was deposed ``in a 10-minute rump session.''
in a riveting moment, lewis had oas technicians play an audio-cassette in which he had tape-recorded the telephone conversation with delvalle's wife, mariela, as panamanian military personnel surrounded her house after her husband had fled
mrs. delvalle, in a trembling voice, described how she had told the officers ``my husband isn't here, nor are you going to find him.''
a member of the u.s. mission, declining to be identified publicly, indicated that a part of the problem for the oas ambassadors in deciding which panamanian representative to credential was that they had doubts about what stance they should take. ``they're afraid of doing something which might prejudice the position their government has taken'' on noriega, the official said
chewning said questions also had been raised about whether el salvador's ambassador, ernesto rivas gallont, had the right to request the special session, with some ambassadors who support noriega opposing it
chewning said those who oppose having the issue debated in the oas ``simply don't want the rest of the world to know what's going on in panama.''
he said the ambassadors had not allowed him or leyton to address the gathering
jose b. sosa, the panamanian ambassador accredited to the u.s. government, said in an interview on cable news network's ``newsmaker saturday'' that he was in touch with delvalle supporters in panama city and ``we understand he is physically all right, he's safe and in high spirits,''
the struggle that president delvalle is leading now is a struggle to get the country back to civilian rule and get the country into democratic process and that's what the panamanian people want,'' sosa said. ``that's why we feel we are going to carry the struggle, carry this fight.''
the panamanian people are going to rally behind the constitutional president, he is going to win this out,'' sosa said
u.s. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the united states had nothing to do with delvalle's decision to leave his house to avoid arrest, but that the panamanian had been in touch with davis by telephone
they denied initially that the united states knew delvalle's whereabouts, but later in the day, when asked if u.s. officials knew where delvalle had gone, they said, ``he is at an undisclosed location.''
according to the u.s. officials' account, soldiers came to delvalle's house at 8 a.m. and were met at the door by delvalle's wife. while the soldiers were telling her they wanted to take delvalle, the president escaped out a back door, the officials said
it was his own decision, we did not do this,'' said one official, when asked if the united states had participated in delvalle's escape
several of delvalle's family members, including several children and grandchildren, stayed overnight at the u.s. embassy in panama city, the officials said
the officials reaffirmed a u.s. decision to continue recognizing delvalle as panama's president, despite his replacement by a cabinet minister loyal to noriega
delvalle's flight posed a dilemma for u.s. policy-makers because his departure for the united states or another country would remove a key anti-noriega symbol around which opposition to military rule could gather
administration officials said on saturday they hoped to marshal international support behind delvalle's presidency, notably among central american nations
high-level meetings continued at the state department, where officials described the situation in panama city as calm
they said the 10,000 american troops in panama _ assigned to protection of the panama canal _ were continuing to keep a low profile
the united states policy toward noriega has grown increasingly hostile in recent months and the sentiment intensified after feb. 5, when two federal grand juries returned indictments portraying him as a key conspirator in an international drug trafficking operation
delvalle had been viewed by the administration as little more than a front man for noriega, but that all changed thursday evening when he broke with the military chieftain
debi thomas' dream of olympic gold turned into disappointment saturday as east germany's katarina witt won her second straight olympic championship and canadian elizabeth manley took home the silver before a crowd of cheering countrymen
it's over. back to school,'' said thomas, who won the bronze medal despite three faulty landings. ``i'm not going to make any excuses. i was really skating well this week. it wasn't supposed to happen, i guess. but i tried.''
while the top two skaters in the world staged a shootout to music from bizet's ``carmen,'' manley was so sensational in the freestyle that she finished first with seven judges. combined with a fourth in the compulsory figures and a third-place finish in the short program earlier in the week, the performance put manley in second place
witt, a three-time world champion from east germany, became the first repeat singles champion since dick button took olympic gold in 1948 and '52. sonja henie of norway was the only woman to do it before witt, winning in 1928, 1932 and 1936
thomas, of san jose, calif., the first black to win a u.s. figure skating crown and the 1986 world champion, skated poorly saturday after doing well earlier in the games
by contrast, manley had the sellout crowd at the olympic saddledome enraptured. they cheered, hooted and stamped their feet when she finished hitting every element of her program
jill trenary of minnetonka, minn., finished fourth. she was fifth heading into the long program, worth 50 percent of the overall score
thomas' bronze was the third figure skating medal here for the united states. brian boitano won the men's crown, and a bronze in pairs went to jill watson and peter oppegard
in addition to the three figure skating medals, the u.s. team had three speed-skating medals: one each gold, silver and bronze
speed skater bonnie blair, america's only double medalist, tried again saturday in the 1,500 meters but finished fourth, well off the pace. she won the gold in the 500 and the bronze in the 1,000 meters
as the olympics winded up its next-to-last day, the soviet union had 27 medals, including 11 golds, while east germany in second place had 22, including nine golds
amy lynn hardin, the infant who won the hearts of supporters from southern illinois to the white house when she became the youngest liver transplant recipient five years ago, died saturday at her home here
she was 5 years old. the transplanted liver amy received on may 10, 1983, had begun to fail around thanksgiving, said her mother, robin hardin
on dec. 11, the family took amy to the university of minnesota hospital in minneapolis, where the transplant had been performed. but the girl returned home jan. 16 after doctors said her chances for recovery were not good
she couldn't stand it anymore,'' mrs. hardin said. ``we made a promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. we brought her home and the family took turns being with her.''
she's at peace now,'' mrs. hardin said
people throughout the region rallied in late 1982 and early 1983 to raise more than $260,000 through a variety of fund-raisers to pay for what then was considered an experimental transplant operation
the rock group kiss performed a benefit concert for amy in 1983 at kiel auditorium in st. louis. that same year, amy received a letter of support from president reagan
if it wasn't for the community getting together, we wouldn't have had five years,'' mrs. hardin said. ``she was the joy of our life. she was very strong. she fought all the way to the end.''
amy was 11 months old at the time of the transplant. at that time, she was believed to be the world's youngest liver transplant patient. that record since has been broken, said mary stanik, media relations director for university of minnesota hospital
ms. stanik said the survival rate of most liver transplant patients improves with time. ``usually, but not always, doctors like to say that you are over the hump after five years, but one can never say never. there are just too many complications,'' she said
amy died nearly four years and 10 months after her transplant. she would have turned 6 years old june 1
besides her parents, amy is survived by two brothers. funeral services were set for monday
memorial services were held saturday for james h. douglas jr., former secretary of the air force
douglas, an attorney and investment banker, died wednesday at his home in this northern chicago suburb. he was 88
douglas, undersecretary and later secretary of the air force under president dwight d. eisenhower, presided over planning and construction of the air force academy in colorado springs, colo
douglas is credited with persuading the senate to approve the design of the academy's chapel, which was controversial at the time, but which has since been hailed as an architectural triumph
the cedar rapids, iowa, native graduated from princeton university after serving as an army officer in world war i. he later spent a year at cambridge university in england before attending harvard law school
after earning his law degree in 1924, douglas moved to chicago
douglas held a high post in the u.s. treasury department under presidents herbert hoover and franklin d. roosevelt. he returned to the army during world war ii
by 1945, he was chief of staff of the army's air transport command
eisenhower appointed douglas undersecretary of the air force in 1953, and secretary in 1957. in 1959, douglas began a two-year stint as deputy secretary of defense. he was awarded the medal of freedom in 1960
survivors include his wife, elinor, four sons and nine grandchildren. safe</head> apparently safe. no pickup.</note>
an oklahoma state penitentiary inmate who had armed himself with a screwdriver and took three hostages gave up late saturday after he was apparently overpowered by a hostage staff member
correction department spokesman jerry massie said the hostage situation ended shortly after 11 p.m. saturday, more than 12 hours after it began
there was some kind of a scuffle'' inside the office where inmate robert taylor was holding two prisoners and a staff counselor, massie said. the four men then came walking out
everyone seems to be fine,'' massie said. ``there appears to be no serious problems.''
he said the hostages, identified as prison counselor chuck ryden and inmates robert king and allen livingston, were taken to the prison's medical unit to be examined for injuries
we don't know exactly what happened yet,'' massie said. ``it looks like the officer (ryden) was able to overpower the inmate.''
taylor's only weapon was apparently a screwdriver, authorities said
linda morgan, a public information officer at the prison, said taylor grabbed ryden, a correctional counselor, at about 10:20 a.m. after they went together to an office to discuss a problem
the other two inmates were out cleaning and painting and entered the office to get more supplies at which time they became hostages themselves,'' she said
saturday afternoon, taylor's request for a pitcher of tea was granted in exchange for allowing a prison doctor to examine ryden. the counselor had his blood pressure checked and ``seemed fine,'' ms. morgan said
taylor had demanded that the warden contact the governor's office and that he be allowed to have an attorney present when he presented his grievances. ms. morgan declined to say what the grievances were, other than to say that he originally approached the counselor with a complaint about his prison diet
ms. morgan said taylor is serving a 15-year sentence for second-degree burglary and had been an inmate at the prison since 1986
warden james saffle had said he wouldn't meet with taylor or contact the governor's office until the situation has ended, ms. morgan said
ms. morgan said that approximately80 prisoners live in the cells in the section of the prison where the incident took place, and ``all are in their cells.''
