eric arturo delvalle fled his house hours after government agents warned him to leave the country, a relative said. the deposed president later vowed from hiding saturday to fight any attempt to expel him
delvalle slipped away on foot ``to protect himself'' _ to avoid arrest and deportation by military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega, the ousted president's brother-in-law, raul diaz, told reporters
i'm going to stay here and i'm going to stick it out. i'm going to fight it all the way,'' delvalle later told abc news by telephone. ``i want you to let the world to know that i'm in panama, that you spoke to me, that i'm not leaving anywhere.''
he refused to disclose his whereabouts
the u.s. state department also said delvalle remained in panama and had been in contact with u.s. ambassador arthur davis
abc news said it had been contacted by the ousted president, and quoted the state department as saying delvalle was not at a u.s. installation. panama's canal zone is headquarters to the 10,000-troop u.s. southern command, which runs u.s. military operations in latin america
the national assembly, with opposition lawmakers boycotting, ousted delvalle friday, a day after he tried to fire noriega as defense forces chief
noriega, who controls the 15,000-strong military and police and is the power behind the civilian government, is under u.s. indictment on drug trafficking charges and claims the united states was behind the attempt to fire him
diaz said security agents under noriega's command had on friday told delvalle to leave panama. delvalle refused to accept his ouster. the united states also continued to recognize him
ana raquel delvalle, sister of the ousted president, said family members had visited him and found, ``he is well, calm, in a secure place and continues carrying out his functions as president of panama.''
deposed vice president roderick esquivel and his family also dropped out of sight saturday. top officials of his liberal party said they had talked to him by telephone, but said he would not reveal his whereabouts out of concern for his safety
esquivel was dismissed early friday along with delvalle
meanwhile, a national strike called by the main opposition group got off to a slow start saturday
soldiers came to delvalle's house at 8 a.m. and were met at the door by delvalle's wife, mariela. while the soldiers were telling her they wanted to take delvalle, the president escaped out a back door, according to u.s. officials in washington
the state department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said delvalle had been in telephone contact with davis and that members of his family were at the u.s. embassy
diplomats said they expected noriega's government would file criminal charges against the deposed president
bereft of power, delvalle told reporters friday night: ``i don't have a seat of government, nor military support, but i do have 2 million panamanians who are tired and bored of living under a regime that one man has governed capriciously, and because of that i call for national resistance to paralyze the entire country starting monday.''
he also urged a worldwide trade embargo against panama
the opposition national civic crusade called an immediate general strike. the coalition of 200 groups has been calling since last june for the ouster of noriega, who has run the country since 1983
aurelio barria, president of the panamanian chamber of commerce and industry, said the crusade hoped to ``totally paralyze'' the nation by early next week
still, most shops and other businesses were open saturday morning, although they traditionally close their doors at noon for the remainder of the weekend
police threw up barricades friday and blocked the short street in panama city where delvalle's modest but modern home is located, refusing to allow davis and rep. dan burton, r-ind., to visit delvalle
other policemen could be seen in the front yard of the small house
at noon saturday, the barricades where withdrawn. diaz then came out and spoke to reporters
diaz said a police officer called at the delvalle home saturday morning and told family members the former president should leave panama
later, he said security agents had also contacted delvalle friday, warning him to leave the country
the united states has called for noriega's removal since he was indicted in florida on feb. 5 on drug trafficking charges. the indictment says noriega allegedly let colombian narcotics traffickers use panama as a base for smuggling cocaine and marijuana into the united states, receiving kickbacks from drug profits
noriega has blamed protests that began last summer and the indictment on efforts by u.s. conservatives to prevent transfer of the panama canal to this country by the end of 1999
american military personnel in panama were on alert and civilians were told to keep a low profile
a texas infant born with almost no brain was taken off life-support equipment that was intended to help preserve her tiny heart and other organs for transplantation, a doctor said saturday
baby evelyn continues to breathe on her own, but shows signs of gradual deterioration,'' dr. joyce peabody, chief of neonatology at loma linda university medical center, said in a statement late saturday
evelyn keys was born with a fatal genetic birth defect known as anencephaly, in which much of the upper brain and skull are missing. loma linda has developed the nation's first guidelines using such infants as organ donors
however, little evelyn never met the hospital's criteria for brain-death since she was born seven days ago, and machine-assisted breathing was stopped saturday, with her parents' consent, peabody said
although three newborns needing healthy livers had been identified during the week, the likelihood of a vital organ transplant dropped to nil, hospital spokesman anita rockwell said
baby evelyn will be allowed to die naturally, she said
it is highly unlikely that she will be able to donate organs such as liver and heart, because without continuation of assisted breathing, oxygen deprivation of these organs will occur prior to her death,'' ms. rockwell said
details about the potential liver recipients weren't disclosed, but ms. rockwell said they weren't at loma linda
evelyn was born feb. 20 in san antonio, texas, to judy keys, 22, and airman todd keys, 21, stationed at lackland air force base. the infant was flown to loma linda that same day to be used in the donor program
anencephalic babies usually die within days after birth
loma linda, a pioneer in infant heart transplants, has sought to establish a practice of sustaining anencephalic babies so vital organs can be used after brain death is certified by two independent physicians. under the hospital's rules, however, no baby is kept on life-support longer than a week, whether brain death has occurred during that time or not
loma linda doctors anticipate that baby evelyn's heart valves, and perhaps corneas will be donated after her heart stops, ms. rockwell said
the same day evelyn was born, another anencephalic baby, identified only as baby john, died at loma linda after efforts find a suitable liver or heart recipient were unsuccessful. he had been declared brain dead two days earlier. in his case, doctors were able to use a heart valve after he died
a sikh extremist wanted in the 1986 murder of former army chief arun s. vaidya was killed saturday in a gunbattle with police, the united news of india reported
the news agency quoted punjab state police chief j. f. ribeiro as saying surindra singh was killed after he was challenged by a police patrol in chandigarh, the state capital
one of the militant's accomplices, identified as harjinder singh, was also killed while another was injured, ribeiro said
surindra singh is one of the more than 20 militants believed to be involved in the aug. 10, 1986 assassination of vaidya in pune, in western india. two others, ranjit singh gill and sukhminder singh, were arrested in new jersey last year and are facing extradition proceedings
another eight suspects have been arrested in india
vaidya was the army chief when soldiers stormed the golden temple in the sikh holy city of amritsar in 1984 to dislodge sikh extremists who were using it as a base. prime minister indira gandhi was assassinated by two of her sikh bodyguards later in the year
meanwhile, police in amritsar, 130 miles northwest of chandigarh, blamed sikh extremists for the killing of seven members of a sikh family in a nearby village
amritsar district police chief izhar alam said the family was slain friday night by six sikhs armed with automatic rifles. the killings occurred in talwandi chamchuk village, 25 miles west of amritsar
uni quoted unnamed police sources as saying the family apparently refused to pay extortion money to the khalistan liberation force, one of several sikh militant groups active in punjab
in other militant-related violence in the state, a hindu policeman was killed by sikh radicals early saturday near the town of ludhiana in central punjab, police said
the killings raised to at least 304 the numkber of people killed this year in attacks blamed on sikh militants. nearly two-thirds of the victims have been sikhs
sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1983 for a separate state in punjab, which they propose to call khalistan
last year, more than 1,000 people were killed in punjab by the militants
sikhs, whose religion is an offshoot of hinduism, claim they are discriminated against by india's hindu majority. sikhs comprise about 2 percent of india's 800 million population but are a majority in punjab. occupied lands</head>
