jordanian and syrian leaders told shultz any peace talks would have to include the participation of the palestine liberation organization in an international conference. israel does not recognize the plo
if you care more about fishing than living, come to muskegon
muskegon was second to last in money magazine's ranking of places to live in the united states
but field and stream magazine's special edition, the ``1988 guide to the best in freshwater sport,'' lists muskegon lake and the muskegon river together as one of the ``25 favorite fishing trips for '88.''
the special edition, which won't go on sale until april, offers anglers tips and tactics for taking big fish
bass (largemouths and smallmouths) and walleyes are two gamefish species anglers will find in particularly good supply on muskegon lake,'' the article says. ``the muskegon river ... features one of the finest river fisheries in the state.''
an article in the july 1987 issue of money magazine put muskegon, a city of about 40,000 on the western side of michigan's lower penninsula, next to last among the ten worst cities to live in the country
most vacationing anglers come to muskegon after salmon, steelhead, bass and walleye, field and stream says
walleye _ and muskegon lake's reputation as a trophy spot for them _ are fast approaching salmon as the area's top tourist draw, it adds
the manufacturers walleye council, a group of touring professional anglers, has chosen muskegon lake as the site for its final regular-season points tournament for 1988
as many as 200 two-person teams will pay $200 each to vie for the $7,000 first prize in the aug. 27-28 tourney, which offers a purse of $32,000
muskegon professional walleye guide mark martin said that last year he took more than 60 walleyes weighing more than 9 pounds
roman catholic bishop donald wuerl says u.s. catholics should help pay the vatican's $56.7 million operating deficit
wuerl, named head of the diocese of pittsburgh on feb. 12, said the deficit was created when pope john paul ii ``raised salaries substantially,'' to help employees keep up with the cost of living
how do we pay for this?'' he said friday. ``in the past we have always said to the pope, ``good luck.'''
considering the size of the church, the deficit is not a large one and could be paid off with an endowment, wuerl said
details of the 1986 deficit were made public at the insistence of u.s. bishops. wuerl said the bishops told vatican officials that americans must ``see balance sheets'' before they would help pay
the bishop also said the vatican's administration costs have increased considerably since 1965, when reforms by the second vatican council added commissions, secretariats and other boards. church officials also have increased their missionary work, he said
wayne county has gone to court seeking an order to seize profit-sharing checks for ford motor co. employees who are behind in child support payments
the suit, filed friday, would force the company to withhold profit-sharing checks, averaging about $3,700 per worker, for 3,369 employees who are more than $500 behind in payments
the checks are to be handed out march 8
if we learn of any payments to potential child support payers who are in arrears, we are going to make every effort to get the portion that the custodial parents are entitled to,'' said wayne county circuit court administrator w. kent batty
ford spokeswoman kim adler said the company could not withhold the checks without a court order
circuit judge richard kaufman has scheduled a hearing for tuesday on the suit
congress faces a confusing choice this week between two rival versions of a plan to help the nicaraguan rebels
a vote is scheduled for thursday to decide whether the u.s.-backed contras will get an aid package drafted by house democrats, a similar one drawn up by house republicans, or nothing at all
current authority to aid the contras expires at midnight monday, and the rebels are said to be rapidly running out of items like food, clothing and medicine that the new aid plans would provide
both versions of the new aid package would keep non-lethal supplies flowing to the rebels at their positions inside nicaraguan territory. neither would provide new weapons. and both would set up a $14 million program to help war-injured children on all sides of the conflict
but while similar in what they would do for the rebels in the short term, the two versions set starkly different ground rules for an impending rematch between the reagan administration and the democratic congress over military aid for the rebels
the democratic version, which house leaders say they are confident will pass, holds out the possbility that a new military aid package could be considered sometime after june 1
but the conditions for such consideration are strict: it could happen only if the democrat-controlled house intelligence committee certifies that the contras and the leftist sandinista government have not reached a cease-fire and that it is the sandinistas' fault
then, the proposal would allow _ but not require _ the party's leadership to bring forth an aid proposal of its own design, and would allow amendment of the package on the floor
the gop aid proposal would give the president, rather than congress, the right to design the military aid package, and would leave to him the determination whether a cease-fire is in effect, and whether any failure to reach a truce is the fault of the sandinista regime
reagan could make such a request as soon as april 16, and it would have to be acted on by congress without delay
a similar expedited procedure was followed when the house on feb. 3 rejected reagan's previous aid request, which included weapons and other military supplies, by a vote of 219 to 211
another difference between the two packages is that the gop version would leave authority to deliver the aid in the hands of the central intelligence agency, which has been supervising a fairly successful airdrop program
democrats, many of whom are suspicious of the spy agency, would turn the delivery program over to the pentagon to supervise, keeping the same private contractors, planes and crews now doing the work
the showdown over the two competing aid packages was supposed to have occured last week, but democrats postponed action at the last minute, citing confusion among lawmakers over the differences between the two bills. republicans said the real reason for the delay was that the majority feared it was losing supporters to their competing version
part of the difficulty democrats have faced is division among outside peace groups which lobbied hard to defeat reagan's military aid proposal earlier this month and were reluctant to now turn around and support a contra aid package, no matter how ``humanitarian'' its terms
some groups, including presbyterians, lutherans, quakers and catholics, were supporting the democratic package in hopes it would lessen the pressure for a future request for contra weapons
but representatives of the unitarian, methodist, american baptist and brethren churches wrote lawmakers last week that ``we believe it is important that no aid in any form be provided that would assist the contras in maintaining an armed force to wage war against the government and the people of nicaragua.''
house leaders were meeting with such outside groups to try to persuade them to unite behind the democratic proposal before thursday's vote, and rep. david obey, d-wis., a supporter the party's package, expressed impatience with the groups' all-or-nothing approach
any theology student will tell you the first thing you learn is that the greatest enemy of morality is moralism,'' obey said. ``if your goal is to save lives and wind the war down, then you have to have tactics and strategy as well as good wishes. i wish liberals could count (votes) as well as they can feel.'' expert</head>
fad health diets and ``marketplace gimmickry'' are giving americans a distorted view of the type and amount of foods needed to help prevent chronic disease, according to a cornell university professor
in a paper prepared for congressional testimony on tuesday, t. colin campbell said isolated studies, taken out of context and promoted by special economic interests, often trigger changes in the american diet that may actually be harmful
too many americans believe in magic bullets. too many corporations believe in profit-rich products with very specific health claims,'' said campbell
such ``marketplace gimmickry,'' he said, does not help americans avoid the so-called ``diseases of affluence'' of osteoporosis and heart attack
in a paper prepared for the senate governmental affairs committee, campbell recommended that the government establish a national research center to collect and analyze nutrition information so americans can receive more accurate information on diet and health
campbell directed a massive study of the diet and lifestyle of 6,500 persons in 130 locations in the people's republic of china in an effort to determine how nutrition affects such diseases as cancer and heart attack
he said the study is not yet finished, but results so far cast doubt on some of the popular american beliefs about nutrition and health
among his observations:
_american studies have shown that a serum cholesterol reading of 180 milligrams per decaliter can reduce the risk of heart attack. yet, another u.s. study showed that a reduction in cholesterol raises the risk of colon cancer. campbell said that in china, the cholesterol levels are far below the typical american level, and the incidence of colon cancer also is low. this shows, he said, that the study showing an increase in colon cancer with lower cholesterol ``is an experimental aberration.''
_excess calories may not be the sole cause of obesity, campbell said. he said the chinese consume about 20 percent more calories than do americans, yet obesity is rare among the chinese. he said chinese average only about 15 percent of their calories in the form of fat _ far below the typical american
_some american studies have suggested that an increase in fiber in the diet may lead to a loss of minerals. campbell said the chinese consume about 34 grams of fiber per day, versus about 10 grams for most americans, and yet the chinese show healthy levels of iron, zinc and magnesium, all important minerals
about 1,000 people, trying to buck the chinese system of assigned jobs for life, gathered sunday at the opening of beijing's first citywide labor market
a mostly young crowd, bundled up in heavy greatcoats, peered at job description posters lining the street and discussed work opportunities with representatives of 22 factories and companies who manned desks inside the ``labor exchange center.''
the center, said deputy chief zhao fenyong, was set up by the city labor bureau to carry out the government policy of allowing people to find jobs more suitable to their needs and skills
those who pay a fee of 27 cents will have their names placed on the center's computerized list and receive help in finding a new job, he said
liu wanxin, of the tienma service co., which supplies tourist items to department stores, said many people want to find new work closer to their homes
others just don't like their present jobs,'' he said, adding that his company found seven prospective new employees sunday morning
li hongjun, 34, said she was applying for a job with a beijing wine company because it has night shifts, allowing her to care for a sick sister during the day. she said she could also take a bus to the winery, rather than commute by bicycle as she does to her current job
a personnel officer at qinghua university, which is looking for nine cooks, electricians, drivers and other workers, said factory workers are attracted to the school's long summer and winter holidays. many, said wang jingxiang, also want their children to attend the excellent kindergarten and primary schools run by the university
since the 1949 communist takeover, chinese have had little choice in determining their career
under a system known as ``fen pei,'' chinese were assigned a job for life from which they could not be fired, but neither could they leave
high school and elementary school graduates were assigned work in local businesses or, if they come from the countryside, were generally returned to the land to farm with the rest of their family
college graduates, a scarce resource here, were sent anywhere in the country that needed them. a student, majoring in english literature at prestigious beijing university, could, for example, wind up in barren qinghai province, teaching english to barely literate peasants
but in recent years, cracks have appeared in china's ``iron rice bowl'' as the country has sought to speed its economic development
the chinese government has recognized that its traditional labor system has deadened worker creativity and kept workers from fully using their talents
it also has split families, especially those of the educated classes. indeed, it is not unusual for couples with college educations to be assigned jobs in different provinces, thousands of miles away from one another
as a result, china has begun loosening restrictions on job-hopping and encouraging the 20 million people who have gone off on their own to set up small private businesses
however, the work units to which each chinese is assigned still regard employees as the property of the unit and often refuse a job transfer or exact compensation for the loss of a worker
engineers, scientists and other trained people in particular have had difficulty leaving their old jobs because of their value to the work unit
that creates the ironic condition that the better one does one's job here, the less of a chance one has to leave it for something better
it's true that if a person has a position of responsibility it will be more difficult for him to change jobs,'' said the center's zhao. ``but if his work unit refuses to let him go, we will do what we can to help, including assist in finding a replacement.''
similar labor markets have appeared at the city district level in beijing, but the center that opened sunday is the first to cover the entire city
illegal work markets have also sprung up in beijing and in several other chinese cities. their purpose generally is not to help employed people find a new job, but to help unemployed peasants enter the urban labor force, allowing them to abandon the difficult life in china's countryside
zhao said the city-wide labor market will also stay open in the evenings and on sundays to accommodate people who have difficulty getting away from their jobs to look for new ones
louis zhang jiashu, bishop of shanghai under china's independent catholic church, has died at the age of 96, the official xinhua news agency reported sunday
mass was said saturday for zhang, who died thursday, at the xujiahui cathedral in shanghai, the city's largest, the agency said
among those attending where zong huaide, bishop of jinan diocese and chairman of the china patriotic catholic association
the ``patriotic'' catholic church in china broke with the vatican in 1957 after accusing rome of interfering in china's internal affairs. the church claims more than 3 million followers in china
xinhua said zhang studied in britain and france for 10 years before returning to china in 1924. in 1960, he was elected bishop of the shanghai diocese, which has an estimated 100,000 parishioners and about 20 churches
the report said he was vice chairman of the china patriotic catholic association, director of the national administrative commission of the catholic church and a member of the standing committee of the national committee of the chinese people's political consultative conference
shanghai's more famous bishop is ignatius kung, who was imprisoned for 30 years on treason charges stemming from his refusal to sever his ties with the vatican. when kung, then 84, was released in 1985, he went to see zhang, kissed his ring and promised to act under his guidance
archaeologists said sunday they discovered the remains of a roman amphitheater 15 feet below london's financial district in one of the most important finds in britain this century
historians had been looking for london's amphitheater for 300 years. amphitheaters were used for weapons training and military parades, as well as fights with animals and gladiatorial combat
archaeologists from the museum of london uncovered the eastern end of the amphitheater's stone walls during excavations going on since last july, said john maloney, the museum's excavations officer, in an interview with the observer weekly
the corporation of london, which administers london city, gave the museum $176,000 to dig on the site next to the medieval guildhall, where the corporation meets
an art gallery and an office building has been planned for the amphitheater's site
the observer reported that the corporation will talk with the archaeologists and architects this week to discuss preservation of the uncovered amphitheater remains
a clash could develop if the corporation wants to rebury the site and proceed with the art gallery and offices, the observer said
london was founded by the romans, who called it londinium. the romans stayed in britain from a.d. 43 to 410
the excavators think the amphitheater was built between a.d. 70 and 140, during the heyday of roman london
corroded coins found on the site may help to date the ruin more exactly
the center of the amphitheater is under the open courtyard in front of guildhall. almost all the area where the seats and walls would have been is under guildhall itself, the art gallery site and neighboring buildings
the excavators say the amphitheater was oval shaped, 100 yards from east to west and 80 yards north to south
that is small compared with roman amphitheaters found in southern france and italy, but about the same size as four others in england _ at cirencester, chester, chichester and silchester
india will halt its military operations in eastern sri lanka for 48 hours because it wants to persuade two tamil women to give up a death fast, a senior sri lankan government official said sunday
the women, anamma david and nesamma vadivel, have been fasting inside a hindu temple in eastern batticaloa city for the past nine days and are reported to be in a serious condition
the women have threatened to commit suicide unless india declares a cease-fire and tamil separatists agree to discuss a settlement in their five-year civil war with the majority sinhalese
a statement by the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the most powerful rebel group, meanwhile, said it was prepared for ``unconditional talks'' with the indian government
the tamil statement, issued in the southern indian city of madras and addressed to the fasting women, said ``we accept your appeal in toto and with immediate effect.''
there was no immediate reaction from the indian government
the sri lankan government official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the halt in indian military operations in the east would go into effect at midnight sunday
a spokeswoman of the indian high commission said she had no information on the cease-fire but added that india had scaled down operations since the beginning of february
more than 45,000 indian peacekeeping troops are battling tamil militants in northern and eastern sri lanka to enforce an indian-sponsored peace pact
the pact was signed last july to end the tamil separatist war in the island nation but it has been rejected by the tigers
the peace accord grants some autonomy to tamil-dominated areas in the northern and eastern provinces, but tamil rebels want a separate nation
jyotindra nath dixit, the indian high commissioner, last week appealed to the tamil women to give up their fast. he said they were being used and ``instigated'' by the rebels to pressure india
dixit said the tamil tigers had the habit of using old women to fight their battles
the sri lankan official said arrangements had been made by both governments to halt the offensive and save the lives of the women. he said that efforts also were underway to contact tiger leader velupillai prabhakaran to persuade him to begin negotiations
his response is awaited. this is a joint indo-lankan move and it is part of the contacts both governments have been making with the tigers,'' he said
president junius r. jayewardene on sunday reiterated his general amnesty offer to both tamil and sinhalese extremists, who have opposed the peace accord
i am prepared to grant all terrorists amnesty provided they give up violence,'' he said at the opening ceremony of a pagoda at ampara, 126 miles east of colombo
the predominantly hindu tamils make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people. they say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese buddhists, who control the government and the army
india, predominantly hindu, intervened in the conflict largely under pressure from its own large tamil minority
thousands of taiwanese rallied peacefully sunday to mark the 41st anniversary of anti-government riots and a crackdown that left an estimated 20,000 dead
the nationalist government owes an apology to relatives of tens of thousands of victims'' of the crackdown, said chen yong-shing, a doctor and activitist who chaired the peace day committee that planned the memorial
chen told 500 people at a church service in taipei that the riots were ``painful history that cannot be forgotten or covered.''similar church services were held in three other cities
demonstrators carried banners and listened to speeches by human rights activists to mark feb. 28, 1947, when thousands of native taiwanese rioted against the fledgling nationalist government. researchers estimate that 20,000 died when the government suppressed the riots
taiwan came under nationalist administration at the end of world war ii, when japan relinquished its 50-year rule of the island nation between the east and south china seas
the country is controlled by the remnants of the nationalist government that fled mainland china in 1949 after losing the civil war to the communists
opposition lawmakers have urged the government to include the riots in school textbooks
in tainan, 202 miles south of taipei, about 2,000 members of the opposition democratic progressive party staged a two-hour march, said party official chang kuo-tang in a telephone interview
protesters demanded official condolences to victims of the riots, chang said. he said demonstrators would place more than 2,000 floating lanterns on a canals to commemorate the victims
president lee teng-hui criticized dissidents at a press conference monday for using the 1947 riots to ``incite the public.'' he said it is ``against the principle of love to repeatedly make the tragedy an annual topic.''
lee, the first native taiwanese to become president, urged the citizenry to leave the incident to historians and ``remove the dark shadows from your mind. have confidence in your country.''
experts, however, say the deep divisions are fading with time
the tension has subdued significantly, especially during the recent years when the government loosened its political controls,'' said lai tse-han, professor of history at the national normal university
the government has lifted 38 years of martial law and a ban on new newspapers as part of its move toward democratic reforms
last year, about 13,000 people rallied to mark the anniversary openly for the first time
researchers say the 1947 rioting occurred after a group of taiwanese demonstrated in taipei to protest nationalist agents who confiscated money and belongings of a woman selling untaxed cigarettes. the nationalists fired on the crowd and killed a man in the incident
the shooting touched off a series of riots across the island and the subsequent response by the government
for nine months, the justice department has given the impression attorney general edwin meese removed himself from the pollard spy case. but now it acknowledges he was briefed twice about the case and it says he never was excluded
in what chief department spokesman terry eastland called a correction, he said meese is only excluded from the espionage case against the israeli air force officer who recruited navy counterterrorism analyst jonathan pollard as a spy
meese is free to be briefed and even to make decisions in the still-open pollard case to the extent that they don't involve the case against israeli brig. gen. aviem sella, eastland said
meese's own lawyer, nathan lewin, was unaware of that distinction as recently as last week even though it was lewin's work for meese and sella in separate cases that triggered the exclusion, known as a recusal
the turnabout comes as a government source said independent counsel james mckay is examining another meese recusal for clues about his motives in dealing with a mideast oil pipeline proposal in 1985
meese hired lewin last may to represent him in mckay's investigation of whether the attorney general and his attorney, e. robert wallach, violated or conspired to violate a federal law barring bribes to foreign officials
in may 1985, meese was recused from all matters involving wallach, but arranged for wallach to meet national security adviser robert mcfarlane to promote the pipeline. investigators say that examining that meese recusal might help determine whether the attorney general was aiding wallach's plan or, as lewin argues, directing it to the proper official
at the office of government ethics last week, general counsel donald campbell explained: ``if you're a federal official and you've hired a law firm to represent you, you should recuse yourself, that is, take no action in any matter involving that firm _ just as a matter of appearances even if you have no financial stake.''
for that reason, eastland said, meese advised justice officials last may: ``i hereby recuse myself from participating in any matter before the department in which the law firm (of miller, cassidy, larroca &amp; lewin) represents any party or is otherwise involved.''
the washington post reported then that the recusal covered the pollard affair. the justice department did not dispute that
pollard was sentenced last year to life in prison for giving reams of secrets to israeli agents. but justice officials still pursued the case, in part, because sella had fled to israel and has not been brought to trial here
so there was surprise and consternation when the post reported feb. 19: ``after being briefed on the case last month, ... meese ordered that the pollard case be kept officially open so investigators can pursue their inquiry.''
asked by the associated press last monday for an explanation, justice department spokesman john russell said, ``i have problems with that account because meese is recused in pollard.''
russell bucked the question to deputy chief spokesman pat korten. citing the same problem, korten bucked it to eastland, who was with meese in california until wednesday
on tuesday, lewin said he'd never discussed pollard with meese because ``i think he certainly has recused himself because i am representing sella.'' expressing surprise at the post account, lewin said, ``at the department, they have known all along that it has been very much up front that he is not involved in pollard.''
while eastland sought an answer, a senior department official, demanding anonymity, said wednesday there was no problem because meese was merely briefed and made no decisions
some former department lawyers dispute that view. one, who once worked in the attorney general's office, said, ``a recusal has always meant a chinese wall. you are not even kept up to date.''
a former justice career lawyer said that, to avoid making a decision by ``a wink or a nod,'' briefings were restricted to situations where the information was essential to decisions in other areas
but friday afternoon, eastland provided an official explanation that did not claim an exception for briefings
he said the client lists regularly provided by lewin's firm ``have not included the pollard case, and so the attorney general is not recused from pollard.''
the lists do include the sella case, and the attorney general has been very careful to avoid taking any action in that case or in any other related case where his action might at all affect the sella case.''
eastland denied meese kept the pollard case open. ``he didn't have to, because it has been open for some time.''
eastland acknowledged that last month and on one previously undisclosed occasion assistant attorney general william weld, head of the criminal division, had briefed meese about the pollard case ``without touching on sella.''
why the turnabout? ``we were confused about the sella case,'' eastland said. ``it was an honest error.''
rep. richard gephardt moves into super tuesday territory with an extraordinarily effective television advertising campaign that touched raw nerves and won last-minute support among voters in earlier democratic presidential contests
while critics complain that gephardt's populist image is an insider's affectation and his hard-hitting ``hyundai'' trade ad is based on bad numbers, there's little disagreement about the impact of the missouri congressman's tv campaign
the forceful spots, created by political veterans david doak and robert shrum, are credited with putting gephardt over the top in iowa and south dakota and enabling him to stop a new hampshire slide that could have jostled him out of the second place finish he needed and got
gephardt is the only candidate who struck a chord, and i suppose he struck it through his tv ads more than anything else,'' said larry sabato, a university of virginia professor with a personal collection of 1,600 political video ads
he had a different message,'' said gene mahan, chairman of the democratic party in south dakota, where gephardt won his most recent victory. ``the economy is not good out here. gephardt related to a lot of people on that. he was talking to the working people.''
in the course of his campaign, gephardt has used a biographical spot, folksy ads boosting the family farm, patriotic ads asking voters to restore america's soul, trade ads promoting his hard-nosed views, testimonials from other politicians, and negative ads criticizing his democratic rivals
most of the spots are accompanying him south this week in preparation for the super tuesday contests on march 8, along with new commercials a campaign spokeswoman said she could not discuss. some ads began over the weekend in texas; others begin monday in states including florida, oklahoma, arkansas, north carolina, georgia and alabama
undecided voters flocked to gephardt during the last few days before the feb. 23 south dakota primary, a development analysts are attributing largely to an aggressive tv campaign against massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
the ad was called ``belgian'' _ a reference to belgian endive, which a naive dukakis used at the outset of his campaign as an example of how iowa farmers could diversify their crops
a narrator in the gephardt ad cites the endive recommendation, contrasts dukakis' trade and farm positions unfavorably with gephardt's, and calls the governor ``one of the biggest tax raisers in massachusetts history.'' in a version designed for possible use in super tuesday states, the narrator concludes: ``those are some of the reasons why southerners are for gephardt, not dukakis.'' pause, then, with dripping sarcasm, ``belgian endive?''
people don't really like negative advertising, but you'd have to say it works,'' said mahan. ``where dukakis made his mistake was in not responding back to him. he just let it sit there.''
gephardt's main television weapon in the feb. 8 iowa caucuses was his controversial ``hyundai'' ad _ 30 seconds of soothing music taking the edge off a sharp message
because of trade barriers, a $10,000 chrysler k-car costs $48,000 in korea,'' gephardt says as scenes from an auto assembly plant fill the screen
the clean-cut candidate appears onscreen in white shirt, tie and black overcoat to conclude his message. if the koreans won't change their ways, he says, they'll be ``left asking themselves how many americans are going to pay $48,000 for one of their hyundais.''
trade experts say the ad is erroneous. they also complain that it oversimplifies a very complicated issue, but that is precisely why it works
it's more in the realm of people's thinking,'' said phil roeder, a spokesman for the iowa democratic party. ``it was a good example for gephardt to use and it obviously worked here. as far as what the actual cost might be, in iowa that's irrelevant because the caucuses are over.''
one reason the hyundai ad and a hay-filled farming ad appeared to reap such dramatic results for gephardt was that they built on the type of grass-roots organization impossible to recreate across the vast super tuesday landscape
gephardt, for example, had worked iowa exhaustively for more than a year, spending hundreds of days there, meeting thousands of activists, shaking countless hands, spending innumerable hours on the telephone. he was no stranger by the time his ads went on television after christmas
his tv spots would not have had an impact had it not been for his foundation out here,'' said roeder. ``it's only at the end that tv mattered and had any sort of impact at all.''
president george vassiliou ushered in his administration sunday by promising to seek direct talks with turkey to unify this island, split between turkish and greek cypriots for 14 years
vassiliou, leader of 500,000 greek cypriots, said shortly after taking the oath of office that he would pursue a meeting with turkish prime minister turgut oza ``as soon as possible.''
but vassiliou also cautioned that ``until we reach a just and viable settlement, the constant improvement of our defensive capability is of the higest priority ... so that we may be able to face the worst eventuality.''
after the ceremony, vassiliou, 56, a millionaire businessman won the presidency feb. 21 as an independent with communist backing, announced the makeup of his 11-member council of ministers _ nine of whom are political newcomers
vassiliou said any solution to the cyprus crisis must include the withdrawal of an estimated 30,000 turkish troops and 65,000 settlers on the northern third of the island
a settlement also would have to allow 200,000 greek cypriots to return to their northern homes and include international guarantees against foreign intervention, he said
the settlement we seek for the cyprus problem is defined by the relevant united nations resolutions ... and is a settlement that safeguards the independence, sovereignty, territorial integrity, unity and non-alignment of cyprus,'' vassiliou said in his inaugural address before the 50-seat house of represenatives
the east mediterranean island has been unofficially partitioned since turkey occupied its northern third in 1974. the turkish invasion followed a coup by greek cypriots and greek army officers supporting a union with greece
vassiliou charged that 14 years after the invasion, ``turkey is methodically turkeyfying our (occupied) land while the occupation troops increase and are supplied with the latest type of armaments
the settlers from the mainland are also increasing, suppressing the turkish cypriots and altering the demographic composition of the population
we are faced by the worst calamity in our centuries-long history,'' he said
the turkish cypriot minority, which makes up 17 percent of the population of 650,000, proclaimed its own breakaway state in the turkish-occupied north in 1983. the state only has been recognized by turkey
talks between the two sides have been deadlocked for two years. vassiliou's predecessor, spyros kyprianou, refused to resume negotiations until turkey withdrew its troops and settlers
during the campaign, vassiliou said he would be flexible in negotiations, but maintained that the issue of troop withdrawal should be tackled first
addressing the house of representatives, composed only of greek cypriots since the turkish and greek cypriot communities split in 1963, vassiliou said ``it is sad that the representatives of the turkish cypriot community are absent
we hope to have the turkish cypriots among us again soon, so that in a democratic, free cyprus, we shall be able to build a better, peaceful tomorrow, for the good of the whole people of cyprus
vassiliou, who built the largest business consulting firm in the middle east, said he supported a free enterprise economy. he also said cyprus would remain a non-aligned nation
rampaging elephants trampled a man to death in southeastern kenya, and a hippopotamus emerged from a sewage pond and attacked a bicyclist on the capital's outskirt, a newspaper said sunday
the elephants rampaged through vuria village near the tsavo national park in southeastern kenya, crushing to death 60-year-old john mwakise, the daily nation said. it did not say how many elephants were in the friday attack
in embakasi, on the capital's eastern edge near nairobi national park, a 35-year-old man riding by a sewage plant was bitten on the head, buttocks and thigh thursday by a hippopotamus that emerged from the waste water, the paper said
the man, identified as michael oboyo akaye, was reportedly hospitalized in serious condition. cruel kings</head>
when the arizona senate opens gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial monday, it will embark on a course laid out in england as a way to remove cruel kings and brought to america in colonial days as a way to protect democracy
but despite the long and sometimes colorful history of impeachment, legal scholars say the seldom-used laws are ill defined. arizona lawmakers grappling with mecham's fate have to make up many rules as they go along
the arizona constitution provides few standards or procedures for how the senate is to perform its role,'' said university of arizona law professor robert glennon
mecham was impeached feb. 5 by the arizona house of representatives on allegations of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official
the impeachment amounts to an indictment, and the senate process to a trial. the 30 senators will act as both judge and jury for the embattled republican governor
but an impeachment trial is not a criminal trial _ it's purely part of the political system. the only penalty the governor faces is removal from office
it's basically _ `you're fired,''' glennon said. ``impeachment is a way to get out of office those officials that violate the public trust.''
even before mecham's impeachment trial begins, political arguments arising from the legal vagueness have abounded in the republican-controlled senate
while setting the rules, the senators have agreed, for example, that the evidence against mecham must be ``clear and convincing'' in order to find him guilty. that's not as rigid as the requirement in criminal trials that guilt be ``beyond a reasonable doubt,'' but it is tougher than the civil standard of a ``preponderance of the evidence'' _ more than half _ for a verdict
there is nothing in the constitution about that and the senators can do whatever they want,'' glennon said
it's typical of the constitution to leave things so open. `due process' and `equal protection' are very vague words but we have thousands and thousands of cases that define what they mean. in impeachment, we have so few cases, it's not always clear,'' he said
senators are constitutionally required ``to do justice according to law and evidence.''
even the definition of an impeachable offense has been argued through history
former president richard nixon, whose watergate activities were probed by an impeachment committee in the u.s. house of representatives, argued that a misdeed had to be dastardly enough to deserve a criminal indictment to be impeachable
but that's not necessarily true, glennon said. impeachment doesn't have to involve illegal activities _ only ``high crimes, misdemeanors, or malfeasance'' in arizona
no court in arizona has specifically defined high crimes and misdemeanors regarding impeachment, but the arizona supreme court has said malfeasance occurs if an elected official commits ``an act which is either positively wrong or unlawful,'' according to arizona supreme court chief justice frank gordon
the trial may look to observers like a criminal trial, but all 30 senators will have a chance to question witnesses, much like a congressional hearing. a two-thirds vote _ 20 senators _ is required to convict the governor
gordon, the chief justice, will sit as a referee and be called the ``presiding officer.'' five members of the house, through their attorneys, will sit as the ``board of managers'' and handle the prosecution. mecham will have his own defense attorneys
and there won't be any attempt to have an impartial jury
it is quite clear that the framers of the u.s. constitution (from which the arizona law is drawn) chose to make the senate as judge and jury,'' glennon said. ``the governor has no right to 12 ignorant lay people in this deal. in impeachment, there is no intent to have an impartial jury. the framers thought the fact that the senators would know something about the case was good.''
mecham also has been indicted in state district court on six felony counts involving the $350,000 loan, which amounted to about a third of his campaign war chest, and faces a criminal trial march 22. he faces a recall election may 17
he is the 16th governor to be impeached in u.s. history; six have been convicted and removed from office. he is the first arizona governor to be impeached
if convicted by the senate, mecham would be succeeded by secretary of state rose mofford, a democrat who is acting governor pending the impeachment trial's outcome
the death toll from a rockslide that demolished a squatter's camp climbed to 52 on sunday, and rescue workers were searching for more victims beneath the debris, officials said
at least six people were injured, one seriously, when a rock wall overhanging the camp collapsed about saturday after a week of heavy rains
officials said the victims, asleep at the time of the disaster, included 27 males and 25 females. they did not specify how many of the dead were children
the camp is in an old quarry outside fez, which is about 125 miles east of the capital, rabat
several hundred inhabitants of the squatters' camp were evacuated to emergency centers around the city
a young man whose body was used for a medical experiment while he was in a deep coma died on sunday, family members said
the revelation last tuesday that an anesthesiologist had performed an experiment on pacal louette, 24, considered at the time clinically dead, touched off a scandal about the ethics of using human beings as guinea pigs
louette, injured in an auto accident earlier this year, died sunday morning at amiens north hospital, his father-in-law, emile collard, said
it was not immediately known whether there was a link between the death and the experiment in which dr. alain milhaud of the regional hospital center of amiens placed louette on a sabotaged medical device
milhaud was trying to see if the effects would match those of a similar case which has resulted in a trial of three doctors
last wednesday, health minister michele barzach suspended milhaud from his duties as chief anesthesiologist at the hospital center
president francois mitterrand condemned such medical exercises, saying neither scientific progress nor the search for truth could justify them
milhaud had told his superiors about the experiment, which he videotaped
it was the second time milhaud said he had used a comatose human being for an experiment. in 1985, he experimented on a 20-year-old comatose man in a chronic vegetative state, setting off a scandal. that person also died, but no link was established between the experiment and the death
at the time, milhaud called such patients ``almost perfect human models, who constitute intermediaries between animal and man.''
the latest experiment was made public in testimony tuesday by dr. jean lassner, a medical expert at a trial in the town of poitiers where three doctors are charged in connection with the 1984 death of a 33-year-old woman
the woman, nicole berneron, died after the removal of a tumor. she apparently had received nitrogen oxide instead of oxygen during resuscitation. a report showed that the tubes of the resuscitation system had been switched
milhaud had informed lassner of his experiment but has refused all comment since the court testimony
lisa carlson borrowed a truck to take her husband's body to the crematory after he shot himself in 1981. in the early hours of the morning, she could think clearly enough only to know she didn't have the money to pay a funeral home
his ashes are buried in the garden behind their country home, the spot marked by a slab of granite on which she etched his name, john brackett, with a pocket knife
she regrets only that she didn't share the intimate farewell with her husband's mother and the couple's children
now carlson has written a book to help other people make their own funeral arrangements. she began writing it after her current husband, stephen, and his three brothers buried their mother in a pine box atop a ridge
it's very easy to understand why people give it away to a funeral home, and indeed, if i had had the money, i would have given away a very special opportunity,'' carlson said during a recent interview at her home
her book, ``caring for your own dead,'' includes a directory of each state's laws on funeral arrangements, cremation and home burial, a glossary of terms and instructions on completing a death certificate. it also includes a listing of medical schools that accept body donations
i really tried to take the mystery out of body disposition,'' carlson said
many states allow funerals to be handled privately, but carlson said there may be obstacles to obtaining needed information on short notice, including some funeral directors reluctant to offer prices over the telephone and local officials unaccustomed to the idea. she credits many in the funeral industry for their help during her nine months of researching the book
she found that anyone in vermont can do a home burial as long as technical requirements involving the death certificate are met. if the burial is to be on private property it must be away from power lines and water and may be subject to local zoning restrictions. the town clerk keeps a map of private burial plots
according to carlson, a cremation could cost as little as $130, including a permit. transportation and a box would add to the cost
the professional services and cost of the casket are two of the major expenses,'' carlson said
in 1987, the average cost of a funeral, including professional services and a casket, was $2,935, according to an industry newsletter, funeral service insider
carlson took on her husband's funeral first from financial necessity. but then she realized that ``not only was it all right, it became clear to me that i needed to do it.''
one funeral director whom she had interviewed for the book called her after his 7-year-old son died
he didn't realize until afterwards how important it was for him to be involved personally,'' she said
most states do not limit the family in caring for their dead, but some prohibit home burial and limit the scattering of ashes, her book says. about 80 percent of the 500 crematories carlson contacted across the country will accept a body from someone other than a funeral director
no state requires a body to be embalmed in every case, but many require it if a person died of a contagious disease, the book says
in alaska, a body may not be closed after an autopsy. in most of california, burial must be in an established cemetery. colorado has no state licensing requirements for funeral directors, so anyone may handle a funeral
in new england, according to carlson's book, there are limits on private funerals and home burial in new hampshire, connecticut, massachusetts and new york
other states where the family's involvement in funeral arrangements may be limited are indiana, louisiana, massachusetts, michigan, minnesota, nebraska, nevada, new jersey, ohio and west virginia, she says
presidential candidates from congress work in a system where it's hard to avoid some flip-flopping on issues but when a candidate can't offer convincing explanations, those charges take root with voters, experts say
two democratic candidates battling for super tuesday votes, missouri rep. richard gephardt and tennessee sen. albert gore, have been the most frequent targets, even trading those accusations themselves. both, as legislators, have voted on two sides of several issues
gephardt has taken fire for moving to the left after deciding to run for president, on abortion, trade and social issues. gore has become more conservative, especially on defense matters
gordon jones, vice president of the heritage foundation, a conservative washington think tank, said, ``there are a lot of reasons to vote differently at different times.'' legislative strategy means ``sometimes you've got to hold your nose'' and vote, he said
but that doesn't mean voters should dismiss flip-flops lightly, he said, and the candidates should provide substantial reasons
the most damaging thing to dick gephardt is his response to why he voted for the (1981) reagan tax cut'' said norman ornstein, who studies congress and politics at the american enterprise institute
during his campaign, ``first he said he fought it,'' voting for it only after a democratic alternative failed, ``then he said he was proud of it,'' ornstein said
jones said gore stumbled when he recently tried to deny voting for an anti-abortion amendment. then, jones said, the question becomes ``whether he remembers his record right, and if he's falsifying his record.''
few members of congress can keep their voting records pure. often several issues are packaged together with neither side getting a clear victory
for example, the house is scheduled this week to consider a compromise bill. liberals might support it because of its general broadening of legal protections for women and minorities, but to do so they've got to swallow an anti-abortion provision
to take an individual vote and say that that means somebody stood for this or stood for that sometimes takes a lot of stretching,'' ornstein said. ``you can't pay a whole lot of attention to the individual charges being made, not as much as to the defense being made,'' he said
liberal and conservative groups who release annual studies of congressional records carefully select votes they believe show the true stance of a politician. sometimes, the tallies are on procedural motions or other technicalities obscure to voters
only a handful of lawmakers get 100 percent ratings from either the conservative or liberal groups
marc pearl, national director of americans for democratic action, a liberal organization, said his group's ratings can help voters look at the bigger picture rather than individual votes. on single issues, voters should be most aware of when candidates abandon long-held positions, he said
i would define a flip-flop as when a person had a consistent position for a number of years ... then recently, for whatever reasons not explained, there has been a change in attitude,'' he said
it might be unfair, for example, to say vice president george bush flip-flopped because six years he praised ousted philippines president ferdinand marcos and now he supports the new government
gephardt was a consistent abortion opponent until he started to run for president and gore consistently opposed military aid to the contra rebels in nicaragua. now they have changed their positions and ``i think it is legitimate to ask, `tell us what the change process was,''' he said
i don't want my president locked into an ideology,'' he said. ``but i think it's legitimate to ask them what were the reasons why.''
voters are willing to accept changes in position if they believe they are sincere, he said. ``ronald reagan was on the board of ada forty years ago _ you want to talk about flip-flopping,'' pearl said
bob canavan, director of the voter education project of the american association of retired people, said his organization avoids releasing voting-record scorecards on the politically explosive issues surrounding social security
there are so many other things, such as committee activities, putting together legislation, which don't show up'' with a vote tally, he said. the organization also questions whether an objective scorecard can be produced,
candidates, meanwhile, don't always see the inconsistencies in their own positions
politicians don't lie,'' jones said. ``they just have an infinite capacity for self-delusion.'' shadows</head>
during the first month of a cigarette liability trial, anti-tobacco attorneys have introduced stacks of documents and presented 10 witnesses. through much of the evidence runs a common thread: lawyers and more lawyers
attorneys for the plaintiff argue that cigarette company attorneys kept a keen eye on smoking and health research, helped shape corporate policy and vetoed putting safer smokes on the market
one reason, according to the plaintiff's theory, is because the companies felt that if they acknowledged the dangers of smoking _ either through public statements or marketing of a less dangerous product _ they would be open to lawsuits over existing cigarettes
the trial of philip morris co., liggett group inc. and lorillard inc., makers of the brands that rose cipollone smoked for 40 years before she died of lung cancer at the age of 58 in 1984, enters its second month monday. her husband, antonio, is pursuing a suit she filed before she died and is asking for unspecified damages
attorneys for the tobacco companies say legal concerns did not dictate research
lawyers are involved in decisions of industry all over the place,'' said chuck wall, an attorney for the kansas city, mo., of firm shook, hardy &amp; bacon, which represents morris and lorillard
he said lawyers need to be familiar with research and scientific developments because of the rising tide of lawsuits against the cigarette-makers since the early 1950s and to advise clients on advertising and testimony before public bodies
the evidence so far has addressed three of the plaintiffs' allegations _ that the defendants knew how to make a safer cigarette but didn't; knew of potential health hazards from the 1920s through 1940s but did not act enough on the knowledge and failed to tell consumers; and sought to suppress or shape in their favor research on the hazards of smoking
the jury has heard the testimony of former in-house and external researchers, top corporate executives and an expert on smoking and health
testimony during most of last week was from joseph f. cullman iii, chairman emeritus and former president of philip morris
marc z. edell, representing the cipollone estate, asked cullman, for example, if the company's general counsel ``advised'' him on cigarette smoking and health issues
he wouldn't advise,'' cullman said. ``he would monitor them, i'd say.''
several confidential documents introduced into evidence thursday appear to indicate the role of lawyers
a letter dated april 29, 1974, from the chairman of r.j. reynolds to an official of the council for tobacco research, describes a committee of manufacturers formed to study industry-funded research programs. the council itself was funded by tobacco companies
the reynolds executive named the committee's chairman as david r. hardy, the named partner in the shook, hardy firm handling the current trial
a july 3, 1974, memo to committee members from another shook, hardy attorney speaks of ``gaps in knowledge'' in the smoking-health field
included is mention of a paper by tobacco council lawyer ed jacob with a section described as ``a summarization and slight updating of research recommendations.''
before hardy assumed control of the manufacturers' research study committee, he corresponded with a tobacco council scientist, another memo showed
a dec. 24, 1969, letter indicates the researcher, arthur furst, had discussed with jacob the work of a british cancer researcher
furst recommended to hardy that the british researcher, h.j. eysenck, a psychologist at the bethlem royal and maudsley hospitals in london, be given money for a pilot project. the letter said eysenck had a theory that ``there may be a relationship between the appearance of cancer for some people and their emotional make up.''
twelve years later, eysenck wrote to jacob to ask for more research council funding, although it is unclear from the letter, also introduced last week, what the project involved
president hafez assad has hinted that syria may be able to help free kidnapped lt. col. william r. higgins, a u.s. official said sunday
the official, who spoke in jerusalem on condition of anonymity, said assad told secretary of state george p. shultz during his visit to damascus on saturday that he had ``some ideas'' about higgins' case
the official said shultz and assad talked about the situation in lebanon but declined to elaborate. ``we can't get into it,'' he said when pressed for details
higgins, 43, of danville, ky., headed a u.n. observer team attached to the u.n. peacekeeping force in south lebanon. he was kidnapped feb. 17 while returning to u.n. headquarters in naqoura from the port city of tyre
the kidnapping brought to 25 the number of foreign hostages held in lebanon. terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, is the longest held. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
a pro-iranian shiite moslem faction calling itself the ``oppressed on earth'' claimed responsibility for higgins' abduction and said he was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the accusation
in beirut, a senior militia official said sunday that higgins' kidnapping has imperiled lebanon's shiite moslem sect
this is the first abduction that has brought the sect's two giants close to a head-on collision,'' said abdul-majid saleh, chief political officer of justice minister nabih berri's mainstream shiite amal militia in south lebanon
the syrian-allied amal has been at loggerheads with the iranian-backed extremist hezbollah, or party of god, for several years, but the kidnapping has increased tensions
amal has viewed the abduction as a challenge to its dominance in the tyre region and has vowed to leave no stone unturned in south lebanon to rescue the combat-decorated vietnam veteran. hezbollah praised the abduction and called higgins a ``filthy american.''
saleh told reporters in tyre that the abduction was ``more of a peril to the shiite community than to the united states. it has been threatening to kindle an intercommunal strife.''
saleh said an unidentified third party was currently engaged in a mediation effort to ensure higgins' release and head off an amal-hezbollah clash
in damascus, information minister mohammed salman said sunday that syria had assured shultz of its continued efforts to gain higgins' release
in an interview with the associated press, salman said syria's policy is to work with friendly organizations in lebanon, in particular the amal militia, to obtain the release of the one-time aide to former u.s. defense secretary caspar weinberger
salman said president reagan had asked assad for help in securing higgins' release
syrian officials noted with irony reagan's request and the recent parade of u.s. officials to damascus. just two years ago the united states accused syria of terrorism, brought its ambassador home and slapped sanctions against it
salman said he believed the turnabout came when washington realized that no middle east settlement was possible without syria and the palestine liberation organization
last october, u.s. ambassador william eagleton returned to his post in damacus
salman said eagleton informed him 10 days ago that another sanction, restrictions on visas for syrians tarveling to the united states, had been lifted
shultz, explaining the u.s. shift, has said syria had distanced itself from terrorism
last year syria closed the damascus office of palestinian terrorist mastermind abu nidal
abu nidal, whose real name is sabri al-banna, split from the plo in the early 1970s. he was convicted in absentia in italy earlier this month of masterminding a 1985 terrorist attack on a rome airport in which 16 people were killed
sen. al gore is looking into borrowing money for extensive tv ads in the super tuesday states critical to his presidential campaign, but a spokesman said sunday he has taken no loans yet
we've been exploring options about borrowing money because we want to have a comprehensive media buy,'' said press spokesman mike kopp
the tennessee senator is running a son-of-the-south campaign and has vowed to spend more than any rival campaign on the super tuesday primaries
but campaign finance reports through january show gore was well behind rival michael dukakis in spending
gore began running his commercials three weeks ago on cable tv nationwide and on local tv in the 14 southern super tuesday states, and a new series of ads begins tuesday, kopp said
to date no loans have been taken,'' he said, but added that, ``our finance people have talked to banks,'' to line up the possibilities
aftern ending january, with $2 million in the bank, gore has boosted that to more than $3 million through fund-raisers and mail, kopp said
campaign finance reports show that dukakis as of jan. 31 had spent more in 13 of the 20 super tuesday states than any democrat in the race, and close to $1 million in all the super tuesday states. the massachusetts governor had $4 million in the bank at the end of january and his campaign says he is now raising $20,000 a day
gore was a distant second, spending only $287,542 by the end of january
that was less even than the $345,280 spent by his cash-poor democratic rival sen. paul simon of illinois who has now decided to sit out super tuesday
rep. richard gephardt of missouri reported spending $482,697 on super tuesday states through january
the figures are from the latest financial disclosure statements the candidates filed with the federal election commission, covering the period through jan. 31
on the republican side, vice president george bush had husbanded his ample resources while rivals sen. bob dole and pat robertson both swept past him in laying groundwork for super tuesday
most of the campaigns, with gore the notable exception, turned their attention to feb. 8 iowa contest and feb. 16 primary in new hampshire, then directed their resources to the super tuesday states in the latter part of this month. figures for february have not yet been released
robertson, the former tv evangelist, spent more than anyone in early super tuesday efforts. his total of $3.2 million included $1.1 million in texas, which was the biggest allocation reported by any of the campaigns for a single state
bush, on the other hand, spent $335,743 in his adoptive home state of texas, and $1.7 overall in the super tuesday states; and dole reported $81,645 in texas expenditures and $2 million overall
aside from texas, bush was putting most of his money, $416,449, into florida as of jan. 31. dole had spent $150,744 in florida and robertson $617,933
super tuesday spending could spell strategy problems for robertson because as of the end of january he had already spent $17.6 million against the $23 million overall ceiling imposed on candidates who receive federal matching funds
the other republican candidate, rep. jack kemp of new york, whose campaign has rowed through turbulent financial waters, reported spending of $11,312 in texas, $8,529 in florida, and $819,311 overall. however, $723,027 of his money was allocated to massachusetts, where several campaigns bought heavily on boston tv stations because that market includes viewers in neighboring new hampshire
kemp adviser charlie black said last week that the campaign does not anticipate any new loans, after borrowing heavily against his federal matching funds last year and in january. kemp planned to run tv ads in seven super tuesday states
the democrats have raised and spent less money overall than the republicans
dukakis, the democratic leader, had put most of his resources into texas, $301,829; florida, $206,861; and north carolina, $146,582
gephardt had spent $482,697 on the march 8 contests, but most of that, $316,822, was devoted to his home state of missouri, which his opponents are virtually ignoring
his spokeswoman, ali webb, said sunday that the campaign goal was to spend $2 million on super tuesday. gephardt has targeted six super tuesday states for tv _ texas, florida, oklahoma, arkansas, north carolina, alabama and georgia _ and will buy in selected markets in other states, she said
the gephardt campaign, which ended january in debt, is ``spending money as fast as it comes in,'' webb said
as of jan. 31, his biggest super tuesday state outside missouri was texas, where he spent $69,809
gore's biggest spending was also in texas, $74,921
simon, who last week announced he would skip super tuesday but stay in the race for later contests, had devoted most of his $345,280 in super tuesday spending to north carolina, where he spent $153,582
jesse jackson had spent less than $10,000 in just three super tuesday states, north carolina, maryland and kentucky. jackson is expected to run strongly across the south, where 14 states are among the super tuesday battles
he has raised considerably less money than his competitors, but his campaign concentrates on the free media that he engenders by virture of his international personality status and his ability to draw large crowds virtually everywhere he goes
gary hart, the former senator from colorado, had spent $37,814 in texas as of jan. 31, and just $12,000 in five other super tuesday states
