millard bowles, you are a walking crime wave,'' said judge robert e. dauer after handing down the sentence friday. ``i hope you serve every moment of it.''
anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other religious leaders called sunday for a sweeping campaign of defiance against new restrictions on opposition groups
prominent clergy told their congregations that the church would become more active in opposing apartheid now that the government has banned political activity by 18 opposition groups. they called for a church-led campaign against the latest crackdown
we have no option but to engage in activities that now are prohibited,'' said the rev. frank chikane, general secretary of the south african council of churches
no matter what the consequences, we will continue to seek the unbanning of democratic organizations and the transfer of power from the white minority to all the people,'' chikane told about 200 people at central methodist church in johannesburg
the government on wednesday banned the 18 black-led groups from political activity and placed restrictions on the activities of 18 senior black leaders
church groups weren't included in the crackdown and theoretically still were free to engage in resistance campaigns, but most forms of peaceful protest still are banned under existing regulations
the outlawing of the country's leading anti-apartheid groups, most of them affiliated with the united democratic front coalition, is viewed as a clear sign that the government intends to maintain a hard line against all political opponents
rev. peter storey, a prominent white minister and anti-apartheid activist, compared the crackdown with the government's 1960 decision to outlaw the african national congress guerrilla group and the 1977 banning of 18 black political organizations
to do a third time what has failed twice is rank stupidity,'' storey said at the central methodist service. ``what the government has done flies in the face of history, exhibits a moral bankruptcy and is a declaration of war on peace.''
in cape town, tutu said he would defy government laws he considers unjust
apartheid is evil, apartheid is immoral and apartheid is un-christian,'' tutu told about 200 people at the bonteheuwel anglican church
tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize, described the south african government as ``illegitimate'' and suggested church leaders would initiate a civil disobedience campaign in coming days
none of the church leaders specified what activities they would engage in, but there are several ongoing resistance campaigns that were led by groups now restricted. those include rent boycotts in black townships, keeping track of dissidents under police detention, and a push to restructure black education
church services to express opposition the government's measures also were held in pretoria and durban, the country's other leading cities
under south africa's apartheid policies of racial segregation, the nation's 5 million whites maintain political and economic control over 26 million blacks, who have no vote in national affairs
high maple syrup prices after two abysmal sugaring seasons have prompted more people to tap more trees as the sap starts running this year, new hampshire's agriculture chief says
new hampshire syrup sells for as much as $43 a gallon, nearly double the price before back-to-back bad seasons. but demand has not lagged, said agriculture commissioner stephen taylor
what's really kept it up there is packaging in ever smaller packages. we talk about the price per gallon but nobody ever buys a gallon of syrup anymore,'' taylor said in an interview last week
the 150,000 gallons of maple syrup sold annually in new hampshire, most of it in gift shops and country stores, comes in jugs as small as a pint or less, taylor said. but not all of it comes from new hampshire
there's some new production coming out of the woodwork in ontario, ohio, indiana'' that is sold bulk to packagers in new hampshire, taylor said. ``but we have the aura _ a geographic chauvinism'' favoring new england maple syrup
state law ensures that ``if you call it new hampshire maple syrup, it has to be made in new hampshire,'' he said
taylor estimated there are 400 commercial maple syrup producers in new hampshire and 1,000 ``backyard farm-type people.''
we will tap a lot more trees this year, as a result of high prices,'' he said. ``sales of equipment and tubing indicate a lot more people are getting in this year.''
sap runs when temperatures dip below freezing at night and rise to the 40s in the day _ conditions that began to occur in some places earlier this month
new hampshire produced 100,000 gallons of syrup in its best year, 1984. but during the last two years, warm weather day and night predominated, and production was around 30 percent of normal
technology is revolutionizing the sugaring industry, taylor said. he estimated more than 80 percent of taps this year will feed into tubing that carries sap directly to evaporators and other processing equipment, rather than into buckets
taylor says higher syrup prices staying around for awhile, regardless of how good this season is
if we go in with cupboard bare, no carryover syrup from last season, prices will be substantially higher than previous years, even with a bumper crop.''
a co-owner of the state's largest syrup producer, bascom's sugar house in acworth, said she was puzzled that demand has remained stable despite the price
i don't buy maple syrup. i can't explain it,'' liz bascom said. ``we made less gallons at a higher price (last year) and we came out about the same.'' found</head>
the brevard county courthouse has been ordered sealed and workers were being relocated to shopping centers and hotels following the discovery of extremely high levels of asbestos
brevard circuit judge dean moxley ordered the closing saturday after asbestos technologies inc. reported asbestos levels as high as 3.642 fibers per cubic centimeter in the office of judge gil goshorn
levels were as high as 0.182 in hearing rooms used by goshorn and judge charles harris, said county administrator tom jenkins
the u.s. occupational safety and heath administration consider levels of 0.2 to be unsafe and warrant evacuation. acceptable levels normally fall below 0.1
3.642 is absolutely alarming. the courthouse is not fit for human occupation without protection,'' said moxley, who moved his office and staff to a courthouse annex last week after levels of 0.175 were reported in his office
ati said it's probably the worst reading they have ever encountered,'' he said
moxley's order prohibits anyone from removing any items, including civil and criminal files, and traffic, child support and land records stored in the courthouse, without going through a cleansing room. violators will be held in contempt of court, said county commission chairwoman sue schmitt
ati officials planned sunday to test courthouse records for asbestos. test results were expected monday or tuesday, she said
meanwhile, officials tried to set up temporary quarters while a decision is made on what to do with the building
the murder trial of christopher scott lawrence, scheduled to begin monday before harris, will be held at the north brevard service complex, officials said
county judge peter haddad planned to set up offices in a board room at the north brevard service complex and circuit judges harris and goshorn were to be moved to the titusville quality inn
the state attorney's office was being moved to the southern bell building
the clerk of county and circuit courts office will have a skeleton crew at the gibson school gymnasium to direct other employees
the rest of our employees will be furloughed until we see what is going on. we can't get access to any of our records and that's our biggest problem,'' said harry bennett, chief deputy of the clerk of county and circuit courts
ati workers will be setting up a ``cocoon'' made of plastic sheeting on the first and second floors of the courthouse building, enabling operations there to resume later this week, jenkins said
brevard-seminole state attorney norm wolfinger said his staff would probably remain in the southern bell building for up to six months
two norwegian soldiers serving with the u.n. peacekeeping force in lebanon were wounded in a mine explosion in a southern lebanese village on sunday, u.n. spokesman timur goksel said
he said both soldiers underwent surgery at a u.n. field hospital in the border town of naqoura. a norwegian officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the leg of one of the soldiers had to be amputated
