as co-chairman of his father's fifth re-election campaign along with his sister kara, kennedy spends all his working time at campaign headquarters or on the road across massachusetts, meeting local supporters, drumming up new backers and fighting to get people excited about a race which to date has only one candidate
whether my father draws a strong opponent or a weak opponent, it's still necessary for him to know what's going on in different communities and for my father to be able to tell people what he's done for massachusetts,'' kennedy said
when news of ted jr.'s involvement in the campaign became known last fall, observers assumed the post amounted to a training ground for the younger kennedy to seek political office
kennedy said saturday he has not decided whether to return to facing the challenge after the senate campaign concludes. and while he didn't rule out seeking office, he said he has no specific plans
if you're asking me, am i going to be involved and active in my community, the answer is yes,'' said kennedy, who lives in boston. ``i am always going to be active and concerned about issues
i don't have any plans right now... i'm concentrating on my father's re-election.'' but he added, ``it is good, practical experience.''
kennedy got some good, practical experience in boston's dorchester section saturday where he attended a state democratic party caucus at florian hall, home of one of boston's firefighters union locals. democrats of irish descent formed the backbone of john f. kennedy's political base in the 1940s and the kennedy family appears to have held onto that popularity
anybody in the kennedy family has his head on straight,'' said camilla duffy of dorchester, who is gathering nomination signatures for the senator's re-election campaign
many of the roughly 100 democratic activists recognized kennedy from his work for the disabled and greeted him warmly
kennedy lost his right leg above the knee to cancer in 1973. he has remained active in skiing, swimming and weight lifting
i'm lucky to be alive,'' kennedy said. his own return to a full and active life, he said, was all too exceptional. ``there are other people who don't have the same opportunities.''
state democratic party chairman chester atkins, also attending the caucus, said democrats would welcome a campaign by the younger kennedy. ``he's been a great campaigner. he cares deeply about people,'' atkins said. and as for kennedy's political career, ``i have to assume he'll have the opportunity.''
joseph kennedy ii gained some attention before running for office by saying he was unsure of the ability of government to help people _ a position he modified after his election to congress. on that score, edward kennedy jr. said he has no doubts
i am one who really believes that public service is an honorable profession. it's what my whole family has believed. i've had a couple of uncles who gave their lives for public service
people who think they don't have a say _ i really reject that. they can, whether in this hall or a parish, a homeless shelter,'' kennedy said
actor bruce boxleitner, who co-starred in the television series ``scarecrow and mrs. king,'' will receive the buffalo bill award at the 1988 nebraskaland days, officials said
plans for the june 18-26 celebration were outlined saturday night at the annual buffalo bill birthday dance, one of nebraskaland days' biggest fund-raisers
nebraskaland days president kim baxter said boxleitner has western connections through television movies and his interest in quarter horses
to be honest, they're not making as many westerns as they used to,'' baxter said. ``it lessens the field when you limit it to people in westerns. we've gone to choosing a person who represents good family entertainment. but it's good when you can get someone who has been in westerns.''
boxleitner appeared as james arness' nephew in ``the macahans,'' which inspired the ``how the west was won'' series. he was kenny rogers' co-star in three ``gambler'' television movies
boxleitner lives in the san fernando valley, north of los angeles
the annual celebration features rodeo performances, a parade and many other events with a western theme. gov. kay orr has designated nebraskaland days as one of the key events in her ``celebrate nebraska '88'' tourism promotion
chrysler corp.'s plans to close a wisconsin assembly plant and its admission that it might sell its acustar inc. parts subsidiary are fueling worker anger and distrust as the two sides head into this summer's national contract talks
chrysler's parts operations were grouped into the subsidiary last spring, but most of acustar's 28,000 workers have been with chrysler since it battled back from the brink of bankruptcy early in the decade, when they granted concessions to keep the company afloat
chrysler workers think the potential sale, now that the no. 3 carmaker is again earning billion-dollar profits, indicates they won't be able to trust the company in the contract negotiations
more than 1,000 workers vented their anger last week outside chrysler's highland park headquarters, waving signs and shouting ``strike! strike!'' at an emotional rally led by united auto workers vice president marc stepp
one sign read: ``concessions in '79, the shaft in '88.''
stepp, who will lead negotiations with chrysler, said he will give uaw locals permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis, based on local disagreements but because of the acustar issue
workers also are threatening to stop participating with management on a variety of joint programs, like quality control
the acustar controversy comes on top of chrysler's announcement that it will close its assembly plant at kenosha, wis., this year and idle 5,500 workers. chrysler acquired the plant last year when it bought american motors
state and local officials charged that chrysler had promised to keep the plant running for five years. wisconsin's governor threatened to sue, and last week the uaw went to court on its own in an attempt to keep the plant open
many of these workers gave concessions and made considerable sacrifices to help the company make it,'' said harley shaiken, a labor and technology expert at the university of california at san diego
they thought they were investing in their future, and acustar represents an uncertain future if it's sold. chrysler underestimated the strength of the reaction and the fact that it has spread beyond acustar workers and affected the entire company,'' he said
one of those workers is roger fitzpatrick, a member of uaw local 1435 at an acustar machining plant in perrysburg, ohio
yes, we will strike,'' he said at last week's rally. ``whatever it takes to keep them from selling it. ..
we're also going to shut down all (quality) meetings, anything that's joint with management and the union. we will not attend, none of them.''
chrysler vice president baron bates said the company is still weighing the acustar sale. he said the workers' anger and their future under a new owner will be factors in the decision
bates said chrysler views the bitter responses to the kenosha closing and the backlash against the acustar sale as two separate issues rather than a snowballing deterioration in labor relations
there is also tension over chrysler's continuing efforts to get more work out of fewer employees
what's irritating workers is not simply acustar. that has served as a lightning rod for other issues,'' shaiken said. ``there's a lot of pressure in chrysler plants.''
workers see another threat. with the sale, chrysler could become the first big three automaker to follow the japanese model of treating parts and assembly workers as two distinct classes
if acustar is sold, its workers face lower wages and benefits and probably won't receive the job protections the uaw won in the three-year contracts negotiated last fall with ford motor co. and general motors corp
chrysler has until sept. 14, when its current three-year contract expires, to sell acustar and restructure itself as a japanese-style maker that builds engines and transmissions, assembles vehicles and depends on outside suppliers for all other parts
after the 70,000-worker contract expires, chrysler almost certainly will have to accept the pattern contract established at ford and gm last fall that makes layoffs for reasons other than slow sales costly and difficult
the contract also discourages moving work to outside suppliers
the uaw successfully resisted attempts by gm and ford to establish separate pay and benefit scales for parts workers last fall and doesn't want a precedent that would encourage them to try again in 1990
the stakes here go well beyond chrysler,'' shaiken said
the pay of chrysler workers, who gave concessions from 1979 through 1983, returned to parity with workers at ford and gm in a 1984 contract that included a base-pay increase in 1987. auto workers earn an average $12-$15 an hour in wages and $8-$10 an hour in benefits
prince charles, heir to the british throne, should continue to speak out on controversial issues, according to a public opinion poll published in the mail on sunday
the survey of 1,086 adults, conducted by national opinion poll, said 56 percent of britons believe their future king should speak out more and only 14 percent believe he should say less
more than half, 57 percent, said speaking out on controversial issues is what charles should spend most of his time doing, followed by 23 percent who feel he should be a diplomat or work full-time for a charity and 15 percent who would limit him to a purely ceremonial role
when asked who they would rather have as prime minister, the 39-year-old charles or the incumbent, margaret thatcher, 38 percent said mrs. thatcher and 31 percent said the prince
the poll follows a week in which charles made news for revealing he has banned aerosols from his household for fear they damage the environment
he was also quoted as telling newspaper editors he had to fight royal protocol to develop his role as prince of wales and that sometimes he wished he were bob geldof, the irish rock story who raised millions of dollars for african famine relief
singer massimo ranieri won a yearly competition of italian popular music with a song about middle-age love, despite critics' complaints that most of this year's songs sounded alike
ranieri, now 37, made his first appearance at the san remo song festival when he was 17. he won on sunday with ``perdere l'amore'' (losing my love)
twenty-six singers competed for the first prize in the four-day festival, which was broadcast live on state-run rai television and ended early sunday morning
the winners don't receive prize money, but some have gone on to stardom. domenico modugno shot to international fame after winning the song fest in 1958 with ``nel blu dipinto di blu,'' also known as ``volare.''
foreign artists such as paul mccartney, who opened the closing night with his song ``once upon a long ago,'' stole much of the spotlight. other foreigners who performed included george harrison, ben e. king, joe cocker, bon jovi, art garfunkel, robbie robertson, bryan ferry and belinda carlisle
however, the foreigners came in for criticism because, unlike the italian competitors who sang live, most of them lip-synched their songs
carmel mayor clint eastwood won a lengthy battle when the state coastal commission approved a two-story commercial and office building on a lot adjacent to the actor's hog's breath inn
eastwood was on location filming his latest ``dirty harry'' film and couldn't be reached for comment about the action taken friday, six years after the project on the 7,500-square-foot lot in downtown carmel was proposed
eastwood's fight with city planning officials was partial inspiration for his entry into politics in a community he considered hostile to developers, and it provided a plank in his 1985 mayoral campaign
he recently announced that he will not seek a second term when his current term expires in may
eastwood sued the city when planners and the council said his project was too bulky, then compromised on the design to gain approval
a penthouse once owned by texas gov. john connally was sold at auction for $225,000 to an unidentified dallas buyer
the buyer, whose bid came by an audio hookup, gained a penthouse overlooking the gulf of mexico with 3,845 square feet of living space and 3,405 square feet of tiled balconies
the spacious, two-story marble-floored penthouse was once valued at $1 million, but like the rest of texas' real estate market, things have gone soft on this resort island
more than 60 units, located on the island and in nearby brownsville, went on the block saturday. none among the standing-room-only crowd responded to a request for a $250,000 bid for connally's penthouse
connally has filed for personal bankruptcy and last month had his personal property auctioned off, raising $2.7 million to help pay his creditors
academy award nominee robin williams will be the featured performer at an american cancer society benefit on april 7, officials have announced
williams will appear with singer amy grant and grand ole opry humorist minnie pearl at the society's annual black-tie fund-raiser at the grand ole opry house
williams is an oscar nominee for best actor as a disc jockey during the vietnam war in the movie ``good morning, vietnam.'' he formerly starred on the television show ``mork and mindy.''
fourteen months afer he grasped his long-sought prize, the governorship of arizona, evan mecham returns to the state capitol from exile monday for a senate impeachment trial which could end his political life
in recent days, mecham has battled to stop the trial. he has said that his constitutional rights are being violated. he hired new lawyers who petitioned senators and the state supreme court to halt the proceedings
but the senate would tolerate no delays, and the supreme court said it could not breach the separation of powers doctrine by interfering in a legislative matter
the people of this state should be as scared and frightened as all get-out,'' mecham, 63, said at a weekend news conference. ``this isn't ev mecham's rights we're talking about. this is basic rights in the state of arizona.''
the conservative republican governor renewed his vow that he would not take the easy way out and resign
my resignation would write a bad chapter in the history of arizona,'' he said as he stood before reporters in down home western garb: boots, blue jeans, a powder blue jacket, plaid shirt and a string tie with a huge silver and torquoise clasp
that would be giving in to the powers who have schemed and planned to put so much pressure on me that i would eventually resign,'' he said
mecham insisted he should be allowed to resolve a march 22 criminal trial before the impeachment trial and its publicity
as governor of the state, i ask nothing more than is accorded to any garden variety criminal,'' he said of the due process rights he demanded. ``i certainly do not think that as governor i should be accorded anything less.''
some members of the senate suspected that what mecham really wanted was to delay the impeachment trial until after his scheduled may 17 recall election, hoping for an outpouring of support from constituents who elected him on his fifth try for the office
but the 30-member senate refused to allow any delay
we've got to get going. the people of arizona deserve a fair break and the fair break is that the trial moves forward,'' said senate democratic minority leader alan stephens
to convict mecham, two-thirds of the senators must find that mecham committed ``high crimes, misdemeanors or malfeasance in office.''
upon conviction, the senate could bar him from ever holding public office again
although mecham is best known outside arizona for a series of public gaffes and outrageous comments which offended many minority groups, he is not on trial for those acts
mecham is charged with three misdeeds _ concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his car dealership and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
the house of representatives, which impeached mecham feb. 5, detailed the allegations in 23 articles of impeachment, the equivalent of an indictment in a criminal case
after his impeachment, mecham was required to step aside as governor pending outcome of the trial. however, he is still addressed as governor and draws his regular salary. he set up offices in suburban glendale in what he calls his ``government in exile.''
secretary of state rose mofford is acting governor in his place
frank x. gordon, chief justice of the arizona supreme court, who will preside over the impeachment trial, has called it ``perhaps the most important proceeding in the history of arizona.''
clearly these are volatile times,'' gordon said. ``perhaps never in arizona history have so many of our citizens had such fervent beliefs on a given subject. we should be thankful that our system of government is equipped to peacefully and fairly resolve such a volatile situation. it is up to all of us as citizens to let the system work.''
mikhail s. gorbachev met with two prominent armenian writers in an unusual personal campaign to allay concerns of armenians demanding annexation of land in a neighboring republic, two activists said sunday
the writers, silva kaputikyan and zori balayan, met with the soviet leader on friday, said sergei grigoryants, a moscow-based dissident, and hovik vassilian, an armenian activist and editor of the underground journal, the armenian matter
they said the writers met thursday with politburo member and propaganda chief alexander n. yakovlev
gorbachev said he'd take the matter under his personal control and see to it that it gets the proper attention,'' vassilian quoted kaputikyan as saying of the meeting with the soviet leader. vassilian spoke in a telephone interview from yerevan, the capital of the armenian republic
the official media carried no report on the gorbachev meeting
it was the second time that gorbachev had become involved in the sensitive armenian dispute, which erupted last week into street demonstrations that witnesses said involved thousands of protesters
on friday, gorbachev appealed for ``civil maturity and restraint'' in an address read on armenian television by a senior party official. in the address, gorbachev promised that the communist party central committee would review relations among the soviet union's more than 100 nationalities
until now, the 56-year-old leader had never injected himself into an ethnic dispute since becoming party general secretary in march 1985
he may have stepped in now as a defense of his policy of ``glasnost,'' or openness on social issues
vassilian said that organizers of last week's massive protests in yerevan announced friday they would hold no more protests until march 26 so national authorities could have time to review the dispute
the unrest has focused on the delaware-sized region of nagorno-karabakh, in the caucasus mountains. the region is inside the republic of azerbaidzhan, but armenians want it to be annexed to their republic
more than 80 percent of nagorno-karabakh's 157,000 residents are aremenian
the official news agency tass and central soviet television on saturday tried to calm the population and play down reports of ethnic trouble by taking up the theme of brotherhood
they carried interviews with ethnic armenians and azerbaidzhanis saying they live together in harmony and that it was important for everyone to return to their jobs
the media said some workers in yerevan even showed up voluntarily for work sunday, their day off, to make up for time lost while they were away from their jobs demonstrating
grigoryants and other witnesses said hundreds of thousands of armenians took to the streets of yerevan last week to press their demands after the ruling politburo rejected an annexation proposal
the decision to hold off on more protests apparently was a result of gorbachev's address and of an armenian central committee decision to ask for a review of the dispute by national leaders
vassilian said about 150,000 demonstrators gathered saturday on yerevan streets to continue the protest, but he said the city was calm sunday
armenian activists have sent a lengthy report to the central government in moscow outlining why they believe nagorno-karabakh should be made part of armenia, vassilian said
grigoryants said that during a two-day visit to yerevan, he learned that ethnic russians had been brought in to replace the mostly armenian local militia force and that 28 planeloads of soldiers had been flown into the capital to help keep order
at one point last week, grigoryants said, workers at the state broadcasting authority, gostelradio, threatened to stop all transmissions unless soldiers were withdrawn from broadcast studios
the workers also demanded the right to broadcast reports on the demonstrations. within a day, the soldiers were pulled out of the studios and reports on the demonstrations appeared on armenian television, grigoryants said
cream pies flew, old flicks rolled and fans talked to to an old three stooges supporting actor when about 1,000 die-hard fans of the celebrated knuckleheads gathered for a weekend of _ nyuk, nyuk _ stoogemania
i've loved larry, moe and curly ever since i was 5 years old,'' said virginia riviera, 30, who came with two friends from salem, mass
they and others swapped memorabilia, threw pies and watched such films as ``three little pigskins,'' ``all the world's a stooge,'' ``dizzy doctors'' and ``disorder in the court.''
i'd go anywhere there's a three stooges convention,'' said riviera, ``as long as i don't have to fly.''
curly impersonator david knight ``was involved in everything,'' joe jerrier, one of the convention's organizers, said sunday. ``when he showed up the place was just jammed.''
knight, an iron worker from palmyra, n.y., who bears a pate much like his cinematic hero's, tweaked ears and performed curly's outrageous antics to the delight of fans who came from as far away as san francisco for the two-day exercise in stoogery
jerrier said nostalgia has sparked a resurgence of interest in an act famous for head-knocking, face-slapping, belly-butting slapstick, pratfalls and endless buffoonery
the original three stooges, created in the vaudeville days of the 1920s, were morris ``moe'' horowitz, who later changed his last name to howard; his brother samuel ``shemp,'' and larry fineberg, a.k.a. fine
by the early '30s, shemp had left in a pay dispute and jerome ``curly,'' another horowitz brother, took over
the stooges made more than 190 short films and about 50 feature-length films until the '60s, said jerrier. moe was the last stooge to die, in 1975
in one room, three stooges postcards, t-shirts, belts, ceramic masks and hand puppets were displayed on tables
also on display were books, publicity stills, movie posters and a canceled check from moe. a stooge trivia contest was in progress when the pie fight _ a highlight of the event _ broke out
i was emcee and i didn't even get a chance to close my eyes,'' said jerrier, 37, a firefighter from gardiner, maine. ``i got four of 'em.''
a telephone call was placed to emil sitka and fans were allowed to chat with the man who played a host of older men's roles in more than 60 stooge films
sitka, who is in his 70s and now lives in camarillo, calif., was one of the few actors who played alongside shemp as well as curly, said jerrier, who claims one of the country's largest videocassette collections of stooge flicks
jerrier said shemp quit because each of the stooges was making $100 a week while their manager earned $2,000
the convention raised more than $4,000 by sunday afternoon for cancer research, said jerrier. ron eugley, another organizer, said at least 1,000 fans showed up
in addition to footage from stooge films, fans were treated to rare footage of curly's wedding, moe barbecuing, the stooges in baseball uniforms in the chicago cubs dugout in 1938, and on the queen mary in 1939
george likar said he's been a member of the national three stooges fan club since 1985
i got hooked 10 years ago, watching them on tv,'' said likar, who flew in from joliet, ill. ``the stooges are great! curly's my favorite. he gets to do all the things i wish i could do.''
israel's navy sank a boat carrying palestinian guerrillas who were planning an attack against israel, killing two arabs on board, police said sunday
an israeli patrol intercepted the vessel off the southern lebanese port city of tyre shortly after nightfall on saturday, police said. three of the five guerillas on board swam to safety and were captured, they said
police said the squad belonged to the libyan-backed popular front for the liberation of palestine-general command, which is based in damascus, syria
but fatah, the palestine liberation organization's mainstream guerrilla faction, said the guerrillas were fatah members
fatah sources in sidon, provincial capital of south lebanon, said the squad had planned to attack the northern israeli coastal town of nahariya to avenge the killing of three plo officers in cyprus two weeks ago
the plo had blamed the feb. 14 car bombing in limassol, cyprus, on israel's secret service, mossad. the victims were identified as col. marwan kayyali, lt. col. mohammed sultan and lt. col. mohammed buheis
police in tyre who interrogated the surviving guerrillas quoted them as saying they belonged to the popular front, which is headed by former syrian army captain ahmed jibril
the front claimed responsibility for a dec. 26 attack on an army base in northern israel by a guerrilla who flew a motorized hang-glider across the border from lebanon. six israeli soldiers were killed and eight wounded by hand grenades and gunfire before the attacking guerrilla was shot and killed
israel radio reported sunday that palestinian guerrilla organizations and anti-israel lebanese militia groups were developing small navies to infiltrate israel. it said guerrillas receive their training in arab countries and eastern europe
the israeli navy carries out routine patrols off the lebanese coast, frequently stopping and searching suspicious vessels
on dec. 11, guerrillas of the pro-iranian shiite hezbollah, or party of god, organization opened fire on an israeli patrol vessel, killing one soldier. the israeli boat sank the hezbollah craft, and four militiamen drowned
three years ago, an israeli navy vessel sunk a ship carrying 28 guerrillas who the navy said were on their way to attack targets inside israel. to forums, sted fora; subs last graf, at their, to fix time to this week, sted next week</note>
the seeds of this week's summit meeting at nato's sprawling headquarters were planted nearly 16 months ago when president reagan faced mikhail s. gorbachev across a plain wooden table in a house in iceland and seemed to forget western europe's interests
it was october 12, 1986, and as dusk crept over the windows at hofdi house in reykjavik and the whole world waited, reagan and gorbachev got into a hot negotiation about the possibility of scrapping all their nuclear missiles
they failed. but when details of the talks came out, western european allies who had depended on a no-surprise u.s. defense and arms control style for 39 years wondered if reagan had forgotten to take their needs into consideration
we don't think it's a fair accusation,'' said a reagan administration official. ``we've consulted with the allies assiduously before and after reykjavik, but there's no denying the perception is there among europeans that the u.s. was willing to make drastic reductions in nuclear weapons, over their heads.''
the summit in brussels will give them a bully pulpit to get their views across,'' said the official, one of several u.s. summit planners who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity
that's not to say we don't want a summit; we think it's important to have this meeting at this juncture, for sound, alliance reasons,'' the official said
it will let president reagan show that despite some of the recent dents in his teflon shield, he is an active and commanding presence. but on a scale of one to 100, the europeans want it 60 or 70 and we want it 40 or 30.''
the europeans' aim for the first nato summit since 1982 is not just to remind reagan of their interests as he heads for another meeting with gorbachev, in moscow in the spring
it is to talk ``through him'' to whoever replaces reagan as president next january and to set the stage for what is likely to be several years of alliance-wide agonizing over the future of its internal relationships and its dealings with the soviet union
the leaders will gather at the sprawling nato headquarters on the outskirts of brussels on wednesday and thursday. the public will be barred from all but a brief opening and brief closing session and several hours have been devoted to meetings without large numbers of aides
at the end, the leaders will issue a declaration summarizing their goals and ideals for nato's future. there also is talk of issuing a separate statement on conventional weapons
rozanne ridgway, assistant secretary of state, said sunday that two summit issues would be: ``how do we stay strong so that we don't make the world safe for conventional war or invite it'' and how to get the soviets to reduce their now-stronger non-nuclear forces?
the europeans fear that with the possibility of a nuclear-free world, they may end up with no protection against the superior soviet forces. ridgway, interviewed on cable news network's ``newsmaker sunday,'' said, however, she believes the nato alliance will always have ``a combination of conventional and nuclear deterrents.''
on an issue prompted partly by domestic budget pressure on reagan, ridgway said the president will take nato a message on ``burden-sharing,'' nato jargon for dividing up the manpower and financial load of maintaining western defenses. she did not say what the message would be but said, ``they can do more. we can do more.''
any private understandings at the meeting will be transmitted to lower-level groups that have been working for months to provide answers to some of the questions posed by a new climate of east-west relations ushered in since gorbachev's accession
the leaders are less likely to dwell on the nuts and bolts of defense and arms control problems facing the alliance in the short run
nato has already committed itself to a u.s.-soviet plan to reduce long-range nuclear weaponry by 50 percent. granted, there is still some haggling within nato on the pace and scope of negotiations on short-range nuclear forces, chemical weapons and conventional forces. but the leaders are not expected to spend much time on these details, leaving those tasks to other officials and other forums
nor is reagan expected to get into a general discussion of problems the united states is having with some of the allies over the continuation of american base rights. talks with those countries _ portugal, spain and greece _ are being handled elsewhere
beyond the internal problems, perhaps hovering over them, is the broadest issue of all: the relevancy of the western alliance at a time when the soviet union is exhibiting signs of major reform and appears to be more forthcoming than ever in meeting western demands _ like one for a withdrawal from afghanistan
the alliance has stuck together for four decades out of fear of an expansionist and untrustworthy soviet union dominated by its military leaders
after nearly three years of gorbachev and no sign in letup in the ferment in his country and among some of his allies, nato leaders are wondering how their alliance should respond
at their summit this week, ``i think it's going to be both a moment of looking at the success that the alliance has had and getting down to the hard issues ahead _ the analysis of the current situation in the soviet union, the opportunities it might present,'' one official said
henry gottlieb has covered nato affairs in brussels and washington since 1980
