the two witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they heard gunshots and were told soldiers and civilians were shooting in the village of 3,000. one arab was shot in his house and the other outside, they said
officials in the ramallah hospital identified the victims as raed mahmoud awad barghouti, 17, who was shot in the head; and his cousin ahmed ibrahim mustafa barghouti, 22, who was shot in the stomach
an arab source, who spoke with a relative of one victim, said villagers also blamed the settlers
in ramallah, two american teachers were released on bail after spending a night in jail on suspicion of incitement, said their lawyer, jonathan kuttab. he said police freed the two, alison glick, 25, of cincinnati, and john benvenuto, 42, of boston, after they refused to sign a confession in hebrew. no charges were filed, but kuttab said police told them they were still under investigation
glick and benvenuto, who teach at a quaker-run school in ramallah, carried felt-point pens and a poster with the names of two palestinians killed in the violence, kuttab said
they were freed shortly after they were visited by a representative of the u.s. consulate in east jerusalem, said benvenuto's mother, marian benvenuto of rochester, n.y., who said she spoke to her son following his release
israel's 24-member cabinet debated the violence. israel radio reported that transportation minister chaim corfu proposed closing the west bank and gaza to the media, but no decision was made
