amy lynn hardin, who underwent a liver transplant at the tender age of 11 months thanks to vigorous community fund-raising, has died at the age of 5
there will never be another one like her, not like my amy,'' said her mother, robin hardin. ``she's at peace now.''
amy died at home saturday. she would have turned 6 on june 1
amy was born with biliary atresia, in which the bile ducts malfunction and the liver becomes hard. she underwent surgery when she was 6 weeks old and again at 3 months, but the operations were unsuccessful
doctors said her only chance for survival was a liver transplant
amy's health became a cause for community residents, who rallied in late 1982 and early 1983 to raise more than $260,000 for the transplant
the rock group kiss performed a benefit concert in 1983 at kiel auditorium in st. louis. that same year, amy received a letter of support from president reagan
if it wasn't for the community getting together, we wouldn't have had five years,'' mrs. hardin said. ``she was the joy of our life. she was very strong. she fought all the way to the end.''
the transplanted liver amy received on may 10, 1983, began to fail around thanksgiving, mrs. hardin said
on dec. 11, the family took amy to the university of minnesota hospital in minneapolis, where the transplant had been performed. she returned home jan. 16 after doctors said her chances for recovery were not good
she couldn't stand it anymore,'' mrs. hardin said. ``we made a promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. we brought her home and the family took turns being with her.''
amy's transplant was termed a success, but her recovery was hampered by a series of setbacks caused by rejection of the new liver, viruses and side effects from medication
doctors like to say that you are over the hump after five years, but one can never say never. there are just too many complications,'' mary stanik, spokeswoman for university of minnesota hospital, said saturday
besides her parents, amy is survived by two brothers
funeral services will be monday at holy family church in cahokia. than human</head>
missi broussard says christ saved her from a life of drugs, sin and barroom brawling through one of jimmy swaggart's ministries
now swaggart's fall has shattered her belief in a man she had thought incorruptible, but she said her faith in god is unchanged
i had this image built of him (swaggart). he could do no wrong,'' she said. ``now i know differently. he can do wrong, he has done wrong, and he can do wrong again.''
broussard said swaggart's confession to an unspecified sin didn't sway her belief in god
jimmy swaggart did not change me. he did not have the power to do so. jesus christ changed me,'' she said
she wasn't at church sunday because she would have had to leave halfway through the service, but she did go to a service wednesday
usually, she said, about 1,500 people meet in the crossfire building, which will hold about 5,000. ``this past wednesday night it was packed. they had to pull out seats for people to sit in.''
broussard, 21, said she will continue to attend co-pastor jim rentz's services. but she doesn't know what she will do when swaggart, who reportedly paid a prostitute to pose nude for him and tried to cover up the scandal, returns to the pulpit
the lord is the one who led me to the church,'' she said. ``if he wants to lead me away, i'm open for him to do so. but i'm not going to sway on my own opinion of jimmy swaggart to decide whether i go or stay
i really do feel like that speaks to most of the church. they're looking to god now because they've learned their lesson looking to a man.''
michael and lisa sexton never saw swaggart as anything more than human
he's a man, and all men make mistakes,'' said sexton, who left his home state of idaho last year to be closer to swaggart and his ministry
i feel nothing but love in my heart for him and his family,'' said mrs. sexton, 21. ``he is a man of integrity for being able to stand there and confess.''
the sextons met about seven years ago at an assembly of god youth group in idaho, where they began watching swaggart on television. they began donating to his ministry about four years ago, and first visited his family worship center in baton rouge 15 months ago
i felt the lord wanted us to relocate,'' said sexton, 27. he got a job at the waterford 3 nuclear power plant in taft. they moved last august to luling and drive 90 minutes every sunday to and from swaggart's church in baton rouge
sexton said he was shocked by swaggart's confession, but thinks it was a good thing
it needed to happen. i sense he was somewhat relieved, because he's going to get the help he needs.''
and he said the sin doesn't change the good done by swaggart's ministries, which feed thousands of children a day and provide medical care and other services to the poor
no one will ever know how many lives it (ministry) has touched,'' he said
after sunday's worship service during which swaggart thanked the congregation for their support, irma keel voiced faith in her troubled minister
i think brother swaggart's a great pastor and i think god will bring him out,'' she said. ``you see, god forgives us for everything we do. he has the advocate with the father. he's my brother in christ.''
you have to forgive and forget,'' said david wilkerson, another congregation member. ``you have to go on in the lord.'' sted this week. subs 19th graf, `the really...', to clarify that entire quotation is attributed to gunson.</note>
it has been 10 months since the trial began, seven months since the first witness appeared and an incredible five years since the mcmartin pre-school molestation case hit the courts
and there is no end in sight
prosecutors say they will conclude their presentation by july, but the defense isn't saying how long it may take
sometimes it irks me when people talk about how long it's been,'' says defense attorney dean gits, one of the players in this long-running drama on the 15th floor of the downtown criminal courts building
this has to be put into perspective. the case is absolutely unique,'' he said last week. ``we are dealing with allegations that cover four to five years. murders don't take that long; it's a split second. rapes and robberies don't take that long
how do you reconstruct a period of time that happened many, many years ago and covers four to five years? if people don't understand that then they don't understand why it's taking so long.''
gits represents peggy mcmartin buckey, 61, who is on trial along with her son, raymond buckey, 29, charged with 100 child molestations at their now defunct family owned preschool in suburban manhattan beach
with time, the case has changed
five teachers originally charged had their cases dismissed for lack of evidence. the prosecution, which once involved 41 children, now focuses on 13 youngsters who have grown from toddlers to pre-teen-agers
and the children's sometimes bizarre stories of satan worship, animal mutilation and trips to remote places have all but vanished
i sense that they have weeded out those (children) who went into fantasyland,'' says gits
the latest child witness, a slender, 11-year-old boy, took the stand last week, telling jurors in 15 minutes what he remembered of his alleged molestation by buckey and mentioning briefly that he once saw buckey kill a horse
in a now familiar pattern, the cross-examination by gits and buckey's attorney, danny davis, extended for days as the lawyers tried to elicit details which the prosecution never sought
details of the horse incident, for example, were almost impossible to extract from the young witness who repeatedly answered, ``i don't know.''
but the boy, nervous and embarrassed, told of being fondled and forced into oral copulation by buckey and said he felt ``sick and dirty'' when he drew pictures of the incident for his mother
davis says he sees a pattern of fading memories. but deputy district attorney lael rubin, who has guided the case almost from its inception, says the child witnesses have improved with age
the children are more articulate. their memories may not be as detailed as several years ago, but they're older, more articulate and less intimidated,'' she says
so far the jurors, who have sworn to stick with the trial no matter how long it lasts, have heard from only five of the children. other prosecution witnesses called so far have included doctors, police officers and parents
the really important witnesses are the children themselves,'' says ms. rubin's co-counsel, deputy district attorney roger gunson. ``and the children have testified very well.''
the trial's duration has had a personal impact on all participants
the jurors, initially restless, have settled into a routine, taking copious notes. many of them carry lunchboxes as if they are going to work
they've become part of the case and the commitment is coming through,'' says gits
gunson jogs and rides a bicycle to relieve tension. ms. rubin and davis found that they had enrolled in the same health club, and they often encounter each other working out in preparation for their courtroom battles
gits shuns exercise, saying, ``when i want to relax i smoke a cigarette and drink a cup of coffee.''
the greatest strain is on the defendants. the gray-haired mrs. buckey, free on bail, sits and knits during recesses, chats with courtroom spectators or thumbs through a small bible
she has her faith and believes very much that god has helped carry her through this,'' says gits
her son, who has been jailed without bail for nearly five years, was granted $3 million bail just before christmas. in spite of pledges of property, he has been unable to raise the necessary $300,000 in cash to gain release
but davis says his client is in ``pretty good spirits,'' sustained by the knowledge he will one day get to tell his side from the witness stand
perhaps the most powerful figure in the courtroom is superior court judge william pounders, who tries every day to move things along quickly
last november, one year after he took over the mcmartin case, pounders marked the date by declaring, ``i don't intend to see another anniversary date. i intend to conclude the case within the next year.''
when a small fire broke out above the stage of the marquis theater, ``me and my girl'' star jim dale kept cool, as did the full house of 1,600
nobody was hurt in the incident, which interrupted saturday's matinee about 15 minutes into the first act of the tony-award-winning musical and sparked dale's sense of humor
you've got to expect this if you come to see the hottest show on broadway,'' dale told the playgoers after they filed back into the theater after a 40-minute interruption
an overheated cable ignited a piece of rope in the proscenium arch, out of view of the audience, said stage manager john bonanni
there was a smell of smoke during the first scene, and after i made my exit, i said, `something's burning,''' dale recalled sunday
then i heard a commotion, and i thought, `that's not in the scene, shouting and carrying on.' i looked out, and people were rushing out, up the aisles.''
one of the show's managers calmed the crowd, which filed out in an orderly fashion, bonanni said. the fire was quickly extinguished by stagehands
after city firefighters made a safety check, the audience was let back in
a few jokes ``got them in a damn good mood,'' and then dale recapped the play's action up to the point of the fire and retreated backstage
dale, who plays a cockney commoner who lands in the lap of english aristocracy, said he ``couldn't resist an ad lib'' in a later scene
i say to the butler, `you haven't got a cigarette, have you, mate?' then i turned to the audience and said, `i promise i won't light up,''' he said
he thinks the incident cast a warm glow over the audience _ figuratively speaking
they love to be involved in something fresh and new,'' he said. ``we can't supply a fire every day, though.''
a swarm of earthquakes shook the desert on both sides of the california-mexico border but no damage or injuries were reported from the late-night tremors, authorities said sunday
six quakes measuring between 3.0 and 4.1 on the richter scale struck between 9 p.m. saturday and midnight, clustered 19 miles southwest of el centro in the imperial valley and 75 miles east of san diego, said spokesman robert finn at the california institute of technology in pasadena
the last three tremors were felt in mexicali, a mexican border town that was shaken by damaging quakes on nov. 23 and 24, said fire department lt. antonio makallon
many panicked and fearful people called, but only those who were in their houses felt the tremors,'' he said in spanish
the november quakes caused four deaths, at least 94 minor injuries and millions of dollars in damage on both sides of the border. those quakes registered 6.2 and 6.6 on the richter scale
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. an earthquake of 3.5 on the richter scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. bowing out of debate next week; subs 16-18th graf pvs with 2 grafs new from kemp</note>
sen. bob dole charged on sunday that vice president george bush condoned trading arms for hostages in the iran-contra affair, saying in a republican presidential debate, ``we shouldn't do those things.''
in a key confrontation before the march 8 super tuesday primaries across the south, rep. jack kemp slammed bush and dole _ the party's front-runners _ as two moderates who would raise taxes and end the reagan revolution
they sound alike. they talk alike. they've supported every single tax increase over the last eight years,'' kemp said. ``if they're nominated, the reagan revolution is over, gone, dead.''
bush and dole objected, saying they have fought against tax increases and for the reagan administration's agenda for the past seven years
they fired back at kemp for what they contend is his casual attitude toward the federal budget deficit
jack's never met a deficit he didn't like,'' dole said
bush told the new york congressman, `you don't care about deficits. you never have, and they're public enemy no. 1.''
on the recent turmoil in panama, both dole and kemp warned that the united states will not tolerate instability near the panama canal
if we've learned anything from iran-contra, we ought to give (military strongman manuel antonio) noriega 30 days to get out of panama or tell him we're going to have a trade embargo,'' dole said, adding the united states should ``de-recognize'' noriega's regime
kemp said, ``if the panamanians want to keep noregia, the united states of america is going to keep the panama canal.''
it was the first debate with all four hopefuls since the new hampshire primary and it may be the last one for bush
campaign manager lee atwater told reporters that bush is not scheduled to do any more debates, including the league of women voters confrontation next sunday in nashville, tenn. dole campaign manager bill brock said bush is following a ``front-runner's strategy'' by skipping the debate
bush tried at one point in the debate to say republicans should not be criticizing each other, but that didn't stop dole from attacking the vice president for the reagan administration's decision to trade arms for hostages in the iran-contra affair
we never should trade arms for hostages. we shouldn't issue these reports and say we shouldn't trade arms for hostages _ the vice president's report _ and then later go to a meeting and say it's all right. we shouldn't do those things,'' dole said, holding up a report on terrorism that was written by a commission headed by bush
bush did not respond directly, but did say ``mistakes were made'' in the iran-contra affair. asked later if the affair had occurred on ``his watch,'' bush replied: ``i think when the president found out what happened, he took the proper steps.''
bush has maintained throughout the affair that he did not know the arrangement was an arms-for-hostage deal
measures to protect the south's textile industry also caused sparks, with kemp accusing dole and pat robertson of changing their stands to please southern voters. more than one-third of the republican nominating delegates are at stake in contests across the south and elsewhere on march 8
pat robertson and bob dole sound like dick gephardt to me on trade, and george bush and bob dole say the budget deficit is public enemy no. 1. i want to say i belive the soviet union is public enemy no. 1,'' kemp said after the debate
democratic rep. richard gephardt of missouri is the sponsor of a tough trade measure that would require u.s. retaliation against unfair practices by other countries
kemp claimed that robertson and dole had said in iowa, ``we'll raise exports of food and grain _ and then go to south carolina and say we're going to put up barriers to imports.''
robertson retorted that he didn't want american jobs being lost to workers in china with its communist regime
there were also sharp exchanges on the question of how to reduce the federal deficit, although each denied that they would raise taxes as president
the problem is not revenues. it's spending,'' kemp said. ``we have a deficit because we have a congress who spends too much money...and interest rates are too high.''
bush, outlining his ideas, said: ``i've proposed a four-year freeze that allows for inflation....that gives the president flexibility.''
dole defended his own voting record, displaying a multi-page list of what he said were his votes against tax increases since 1975. he complained that some campaign ads distort his record on taxes _ a reference to bush ads _ and then hit at bush directly
i've been leading the efforts to reduce tax rates,'' dole said. ``you don't go the bush route. it's a four-year cop-out...we've got to reduce the deficit ... no one in this group is advocating raising taxes.''
later, bush fired back at dole, saying the kansas republican's plan for a one-year spending freeze would hurt defense
it will cut into the muscle on defense,'' bush told dole
and he defended his own four-year idea: ``i wouldn't call it a cop-out. it disciplines the spending side.''
robertson said the problem is not one of economics
it's a question of will,'' he said, asking if congress can make hard decision to cut spending
robertson, who has spent much of the past two weeks explaining various statements on missiles in cuba, hostages in lebanon and the source of the expose of problems afflicting fellow tv evangelist jimmy swaggart, said the press is a big problem for candidates
i know it's very difficult dealing with the press of america to get the truth out. they love to distort our words,'' robertson said. ``we are making it so difficult in our society for anyone to serve.''
the debate was sponsored by the atlanta journal-constitution newspapers, moderated by the papers' washington correspondent john mashek and televised live on the cable news network. the democrats took part in a similar debate on saturday
the newspapers sponsored a similar forum saturday night for the six democratic presidential candidates
most of the nation enjoyed sunny skies sunday, with temperatures seasonably cool in the northeast and seasonably mild in many other sections
light snow fell in scattered sections of wisconsin and upper michigan and rain dampened the southern coast of california and parts of nevada. a few patches of dense fog remained along the texas gulf coast
about one-third of an inch of rain fell at lovelock, nev., and los angeles during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est. an inch of snow fell at houghton, mich., during the same period
at noon, temperatures were in the 30s in much of new england, the 30s and 40s from the great lakes through the upper missouri valley, and the 40s and 50s in the pacific northwest. across the south, noontime temperatures were in the 60s and 70s across florida, the 70s and low 80s in much of texas and the 60s and 70s across the desert southwest and southern california
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 25 at jackson, wyo., and limestone, maine, to 84 at cotulla, texas. the low for the nation sunday morning was 7 below zero at houlton, maine
for monday, snow showers were predicted in the lower great lakes, the upper ohio valley and upper michigan, while rain showers were expected to fall in much of california and be widely scattered in idaho and utah
highs will be in the teens and 20s in northern maine, upper michigan, wisconsin and much of minnesota; the 30s and 40s from southern maine across maryland, the remainder of the great lakes, the ohio valley, the central mississippi valley, the northern half of the plains and the northern rockies; the 70s from southern georgia and florida across the lower mississippi valley; and in the 70s and 80s in texas and the desert southwest. elsewhere, the highs will generally reach the 50s and 60s. on two iranian cities. pickup 4th pvs: tehran's war ... deletes last four grafs which moved up and edits to trim.</note>
iranian warplanes, usually crippled by shortages of spare parts, bombed three key economic targets in iraq on sunday. iraq retaliated with air raids on two iranian cities
baghdad's state radio said iraqi jets bombed the cities of hamadan in eastern iran and dezful in the southeast in simultaneous raids at 9 p.m
the broadcast, monitored in nicosia, said the attacks were in retaliation for ``recent atrocities and crimes committed by the charlatans of iran.''
iran did not immediately confirm the iraqi raids
in a separate dispatch, the iraqi news agency said iranian artillery over the weekend shelled ``purely civilian targets'' in six iraqi border towns and cities. it said said several people were killed or wounded but gave no casualty figures
an earlier communique said two women and a child were killed and several people, including four women, were wounded in sunday's shelling. it said seven civilians were killed and 16 wounded in basra and al-qurna on saturday
tehran's war information headquarters said in a statement that iranian warplanes bombed a petrochemical plant in the southern port of basra, oil installations in abul khassib and a bridge linking umm rassas island, in the disputed shatt al-arab waterway, with mainland iraq
the tiny island is a forward iraqi position southeast of basra on the southern sector of the front with iran
all iranian planes returned safely to base from the ``successful'' midmorning raids, said the communique, broadcast by tehran radio and monitored in nicosia
an exchange of air raids that began saturday have prompted fears that a new round of the ``war of the cities'' is beginning
thousands of civilians have been killed in iraq and iran during such attacks. hostilities on population centers generally are preceded by accusations and warnings similar to those tehran and baghdad exchanged this weekend
the iranian air force was out of action for most of 1987. in january, iranian warplanes resumed combat missions against iraq, an indication that tehran had somehow acquired spare parts for its u.s.-built jets
western military analysts say iran has about 70 operational combat aircraft, including f-4 and f-5 fighter-bombers and f-14 interceptors
iraq, with more than 500 soviet and french warplanes, has maintained air supremacy in the 7-year-old gulf war
the iranian war communique said the raids sunday were in retaliation for iraqi strikes the day before on civilian targets in a tehran suburb and in the town of saghez, in the northwestern azerbaijan province
iran's islamic republic news agency reported 25 civilians killed and an unspecified number wounded in the iraqi raids saturday
the iraqi news agency denied iraq hit any civilians targets over the weekend
iraqi air force commander air marshal hamid shaaban also warned the iranians against carrying out their threats
it is an illusion that iran believes iraq will succumb to threats of attacking the cities,'' shaaban said in an interview with baghdad's official ath-thawra newspaper
shaaban said iraq had drawn plans to ``strike at strategic iranian targets and also at the nests, where the rotten heads are being sheltered.''
that was a reference to headquarters of iranian leaders
a 77-year-old soviet jew who battled for 13 years to leave the soviet union embraced his daughter when he arrived sunday in israel
some of us managed to get out _ many are still left behind,'' said mathematician naum meiman, referring to soviet emigration policies
meiman arrived in israel the same day as another leading soviet jewish activist, electrical engineer lev shapiro, who came here with his wife and two children
meiman hugged his daughter, olga plam, 50, of boulder, colo., after she arrived at ben gurion airport aboard a flight from the united states. she left the soviet union 14 years ago and had not seen her father since then
soviet authorities said they delayed meiman's emigration request because of his ``access to state secrets.'' meiman had worked in classified mathematical calculations in 1955
meiman linked his release to the policy of glasnost _ greater political openness on some topics _ initiated by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
it is true that it's easier to breathe in the soviet union nowadays, after glasnost,'' he said. ``however, in essence nothing has changed.''
the soviet union allowed 8,011 jews to emigrate in 1987, up from less than a thousand annually in recent years but still far short of the more than 50,000 permitted to leave in 1979
meiman was met by representatives of the weizman institute of science and tel aviv university. both institutions have offered the scientist opportunities to continue his work in israel, where meiman plans to settle
meiman left moscow friday and rested in vienna saturday. his wife, inna kitrosskaya, struggled for years for an exit visa for cancer treatment in the united states. she received permission and left the soviet union last year, but died 15 days later of a stroke
meiman was not allowed to accompany his wife or to attend her funeral
shapiro, of leningrad, was accompanied by his wife leah, 38, his son yisrael, 13, and the 9-year-old daughter naomi
the shapiro family, which had been refused emigration permits for 11 years, gained international prominence when naomi wrote a letter to gorbachev, saying:
you are known as a kind and good grandfather. why don't you let me meet my grandparents who live in israel?''
prime minister margaret thatcher of britain and u.s. and french authorities also intervened on behalf of the shapiros. with diaz saying delvalle not with family, telephoning international leaders. pickup 11th pvs: `the panamanian ...</note>
deposed president eric arturo delvalle stayed in hiding sunday and defied gen. manuel antonio noriega, the military strongman who ousted him and ordered him out of the country
the ex-president's whereabouts were a closely guarded secret, but family members said he was in a ``safe and secure place'' in panama, in ``good spirits'' and determined to regain his job
i am going to stay here (and) stick it out,'' delvalle told abc television in a telephone interview saturday night. ``i'm going to fight it all the way.''
delvalle did not reveal his hiding place
roderick esquivel, delvalle's vice president, also was in hiding
both men were ousted from office early friday in an action by the national legislative assembly orchestrated by noriega, the defense forces chief
delvalle ignited the latest crisis in eight months of continuing civil unrest in panama on thursday when he tried to fire noriega, who is charged in florida with corruption and narcotics trafficking. the united states also has urged noriega to step down as military chief
on friday, delvalle returned to his home in an upper-class neighborhood. police surrounded the house friday evening and delvalle's telephones were cut, leaving him incommunicado and under an undeclared house arrest
sometime that night, he reportedly climbed over a patio wall at the rear of the house and escaped through a neighbor's yard, avoiding the policemen who had been posted on the street in front of his home
raul diaz, a brother-in-law, and other family members said military officials had warned delvalle that if he didn't leave the country voluntarily he would be arrested and forcibly deported
diaz said sunday that delvalle was telephoning leaders throughout the world seeking their support
he said delvalle was not with his wife and three children, but that all were safe. ``they are in one place and he is alone in another,'' diaz said
the u.s. state department said saturday some of delvalle's children or grandchildren were at the american embassy or the home of u.s. ambassador arthur davis. the u.s. embassy declined to comment sunday on that report
the panamanian government claimed u.s. officials were hiding delvalle at an american military installation in panama
but gabriel lewis, a former panamanian ambassador to washington, said sunday he was ``under the protection of a good panamanian family and they will never find him.''
cynthia farrell, a spokeswoman for the u.s. embassy, said she could not ``confirm or deny anything.'' she said the embassy was under orders from washington ``not to discuss the situation.''
delvalle's hopes of regaining the presidency suffered a setback saturday night when the permanent council of the organization of american states, meeting in washington, declined to take any action on panama
delvalle and the reagan administration in washington had hoped the oas would agree to impose trade sanctions against panama, or at least approve a resolution condemning the president's ouster by the military
on the eve of a planned nationwide protest strike, priests in roman catholic churches throughout the country read a communique to parishoners from archbishop marcos g. mcgrath
the communique, first issued two days ago, decried ``corruption (that has) spread throughout the public and private sectors'' of panama and said the events of the past few days ``had deepened the crisis and damaged the credibility of the government and the constitutional process.''
but the archbishop urged his followers not to resort to violence in an attempt to resolve what he called ``the grave national and international problems'' facing panama
the strike was called by the national civic crusade, a coalition of about 200 professional, business, labor and political groups that has been seeking noriega's ouster since last june
crusade leaders said they hoped to ``totally paralyze'' the country early this week, but there were indications the strike would not meet its goal
osvaldo velasquez, president of the panama human rights commission, predicted sunday that many store owners would open for business monday ``out of fear of government repression.''
he said ``military people'' already had threatened some businessmen, telling them they would ``kick in their doors'' if they tried to close monday
delvalle was dismissed by the legislative assembly in a tumultuous, 10-minute meeting friday, about seven hours after he went on national television thursday afternoon and announced he had fired noriega
noriega's followers command a majority of 45 seats in the 67-member assembly. delvalle's backers boycotted the session, leaving the outcome a foregone conclusion. issues</head>
democratic presidential candidate paul simon got the highest rating from an environmental group sunday, but no candidate in either party graded better than fair on the southern environmental assembly's ``toxics report card.''
six of the candidates _ all the republicans and two democrats _ got ``failing'' grades from the group made up of 10 environmental organizations from southern states that held a two-day conference in atlanta
the assembly graded simon, a senator from illinois, at 76 percent on issues such as reducing use of toxic chemicals, cleaning up dumpsites and recycling waste
but according to the study released sunday, that grade only rates as ``fair.'' none of the democratic or republican candidates scored in the ``good'' or ``excellent'' categories
republican candidates scored much lower than democrats, with sen. bob dole of kansas getting the highest score at only 18 percent. vice president george bush was next at 8 percent, followed by rep. jack kemp of new york, 4 percent, and former television evangelist pat robertson, 3 percent
among democrats, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee trailed simon with a rating of 72 percent. gore and simon were the only two candidates to appear at a forum saturday before the assembly, which figured into their ratings
jesse jackson was next at 64 percent, followed by rep. richard gephardt of missouri, 60 percent; former sen. gary hart of colorado, 50 percent; and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, 47 percent
the assembly's report card said the grades were based on a candidate's ``past voting records, their written responses to our questions and their personal presentations'' to a toxic prevention conference
ninety to 100 percent was considered ``excellent,'' 80-89 percent ``good,'' 70-79 percent ``fair,'' 60-69 percent ``poor,'' and below 59 percent ``failure.''
patty frase, an arkansas enviromental congress member who attended the weekend conference, said the ratings show that the 1988 candidates are not addressing environmental issues
these candidates debate about many important issues, but they neglect to address the environment,'' ms. frase said. ``how can we focus on national defense when we can't defend our drinking water supplies against chemicals that cause birth defects and cancer?''
an estimated 100,000 people demonstrated peacefully sunday to protest an art exhibition in which a print of marilyn monroe's face was imposed on a picture of the virgin of guadalupe, mexico's patron saint
the demonstration was organized by four roman catholic religious organizations and the people gathered in the capital's main zocalo square. they then marched five miles to the basilica at la villa, where an image of the virgin of guadalupe is enshrined
many marchers carried signs denouncing the museum of modern art exhibition. the museum is run by the institute of fine arts, an agency of the department of education
on jan. 23, about 1,000 people chanting ``long live christ the king!'' stormed the museum in the city's central chapultepec park and authorities closed the exhibit by painter rolando de la rosa
the museum director, jorge alberto manrique, resigned last thursday at the government's request. manrique had criticized the closing of the exhibition
more than 100 mexican artists and intellectuals expressed in a statement their ``profound indignation'' and called for manrique's reinstatement
more than 90 percent of mexico's 80 million people are catholics
in one work, de la rosa, 36, superimposed the face of the late actress marilyn monroe on an image of the virgin of guadalupe
in another, styled after leonardo da vinci's ``last supper,'' jesus christ had the face of the late mexican actor and singer pedro infante. in ``the sacred family,'' the baby jesus was replaced by a soccer ball
a welsh nationalist group claimed responsibility sunday for four incendiary attacks on offices of real estate firms that have been selling vacation homes in wales to english people
four offices in the english city of chester near the welsh border were damaged in the saturday night attacks
police said the incendiary devices were placed through the letterboxes of the buildings
a group calling itself meibion glyndwr (sons of glendower, in the welsh language), asserted responsibility in a telephone call to a journalist, saying speculators and ``collaborators'' must get out of wales
named after the 15th century welshman owen glendower who failed in a bid to win independence from the english, the organization has previously claimed responsibility for starting fires at english-owned vacation cottages in wales
no arrests have been made
