a british airways jumbo jet carrying 281 passengers to the united states sunday returned to britain and made an emergency landing because its wing slats malfunctioned, an airline spokesman said
a piece of a wing flap fell from the jet as it landed at heathrow airport and two runways were closed temporarily for inspection but no debris was found, according to press association, the british domestic news agency
the boeing 747 took off just after noon. shortly into the flight the pilot found he could not retract the slats on one wing, said the spokesman
wing slats project at an angle at the edge of each wing. by increasing the area of the wing, the slats increase a plane's lift
the airline spokesman said the pilot dumped the aircraft's fuel and returned to london about an hour later
the wing slats would not go back in but the problem would not have caused any serious control difficulties,'' he said
the pilot decided to return as a precaution and because he did not want to fly the atlantic with a fault on the aircraft. there was no danger and the aircraft made a perfectly normal landing.''
british airways said the passengers would either be flown to the united states on another one of its aircraft or rebooked on another airline
the plane had been heading to washington, d.c., and pittsburgh
vice president george bush is planning to skip the league of women voters' debate next week in nashville, his campaign manager said sunday, in what one opposing camp called a ``front-runner's strategy.''
at this time, there are no debates on the schedule,'' lee atwater told reporters after a debate sunday in atlanta. ``we're simply at a point where we've got 20 states; you've got to maintain control of your schedule.''
bush was the last republican candidate to agree to participate the league's first debate in new hampshire two weeks ago. he had not publicly committed to attending the league's debate in nashville next sunday
atwater said bush had no plans to participate in future debates but added ``never say never.''
the league has also scheduled two debates _ one for the republican candidates and one for the democrats _ later in the primary season
senate minority leader bob dole would like to debate bush one-on-one, his campaign said after the atlanta debate on sunday
we're looking for a one-on-one debate with the vice president, '' said dole campaign manager bill brock, ``but i think he's following a front-runner's strategy.''
bush is far ahead in the polls on the primaries to be held on march 8, dubbed super tuesday, when nearly a third of the delegates to the gop convention
the democratic league debate is also scheduled next sunday in nashville. the gop debate was moved by the league from its original saturday date to sunday to accomodate candidates' schedules
the south carolina gop primary will be held on saturday
travellers were frustrated sunday by a new wave of airport and railway personnel strikes while italians had few newspapers to read about their olympic skiing hero alberto tomba
alitalia, italy's state-run airline, canceled hundreds of flights to and from rome's airports because of a 24-hour strike by ground personnel. it was the latest in a series of walkouts to protest lack of progress in contract renewal negotiations
alitalia's intercontinental flights and its connections to italy's islands operated normally, as did flights by other airlines. passengers, however, often had to wait for more than hour for their baggage
new contract talks are set to begin monday
long-distance train service from rome's main station suffered disruptions from a 24-hour strike by railway employees that started at 9 p.m
italy's major daily newspapers did not publish sunday as a result of a 48-hour nationwide walkout by journalists protesting stalemated contract talks. only a few regional papers exempt from the strike came out sunday
television and radio ran limited news broadcasts sunday without film reports. on monday, television and radio stations are to cancel all newscasts
the journalists' strike prevented most italians from reading about the exploits of tomba, who won his second olympic gold medal saturday in alpine skiing
paese sera, one of the dailies exempt from the strike, ran a front-page headline saying ``alberto tomba is already a legend.'' regulators</head>
five u.s. senators who accepted a total of $297,000 in contributions from an arizona company and its employees met with federal bank examiners investigating one of its subsidiaries, a newspaper reported sunday
within three months of the meeting, examiners backed off and ultimately cleared the subsidiary, lincoln savings and loan association of irvine, calif., of wrongdoing, the detroit news quoted unidentified sources as saying
the thrift is owned by phoenix, ariz.-based american continental corp. executives of the company and its subsidiaries made the donations over the past several years, the newspaper reported
those accepting the contributions and the amounts, according to the news, were: alan cranston, d-calif., $41,900; dennis deconcini, d-ariz., $43,000; john glenn, d-ohio, $34,000; john mccain, r-ariz., $112,000; and don riegle, d-mich., $66,100
riegle said there was no connection between the contribution toward his 1988 re-election campaign and the april 9, 1987, meeting in which he and the four other senators discussed the investigation with federal home loan bank board examiners
if there was the slightest suggestion or hint that somehow somebody was going to contribute in return for some kind of favorable consideration, we don't want that money,'' riegle said. ``i wouldn't accept it.''
aides to the other senators said none was available to comment late last week, the newspaper reported
the banking investigators were looking into high-risk investments made by lincoln that could threaten its solvency, the news said
the contributions were permissible under federal election laws. riegle's campaign chairman, kevin gottlieb, said the timing of the donations and the meeting with regulators was ``an interesting coincidence.''
riegle told the newspaper he attended the meeting because he is a senior member of the senate banking committee and wanted to ensure lincoln savings received a fair review
he said he was invited to the meeting by the other senators and was concerned lincoln was being harassed
the newspaper quoted an unidentified source as saying that after the meeting, the probe changed direction
san francisco bank examiners ``were ready to ask for an enforcement action against lincoln,'' an unidentified california bankig official was quoted as saying. ``but that has changed. the scope of the examination has changed.''
american continental spokesman andy baer characterized the events differently
i wouldn't say (the examiners) backed off; i would say there is a new spirit of cooperation,'' baer said
the final bank examiner's report recommended no sanctions against lincoln, said robert kielty, american continental's corporate counsel. cockpit</head> spokeswoman, flight resuming. no pickup.</note>
a midway airlines 737 flying from tampa to chicago made an unscheduled landing here sunday after its pilot reported an electrical problem that produced smoke in the cockpit, authorities said
flight 793, with 119 passengers and five crew members aboard, landed safely at gainesville regional airport about 1:20 p.m. with no injuries reported, said federal aviation administration shift supervisor v.h. steed
it was a precautionary measure,'' he said. ``none of the passengers were ever in danger.''
gainesville fire department spokesman stew schwartz said the pilot asked that fire crews be ready because of an unusual odor and some smoke in the cockpit
midway spokeswoman sandra allen in chicago said smoke apparently came from an electrical problem
at this point, we don't know exactly what caused the smoke,'' she said. ``two of our mechanics from miami are being sent to gainesville to inspect the plane.''
the passengers waited in the airport's terminal for about two hours until another midway plane was flown in and the flight resumed, ms. allen said. the boeing jet will remain in gainesville until the mechanics declare it fit to fly, she said. officials</head> woman. no pickup.</note>
one of two american hostages released sunday after their arrests by israeli authorities in the occupied west bank said the most frightening part of the ordeal was being denied access to u.s. authorities or an attorney
it was confusion and of course fright, because when you're denied access to a lawyer and you're denied access to your own government, it's frightening to realize that you're cut off from any sort of legal protection,'' alison glick, 25, said in a telephone interview with wcpo-tv in cincinnati
ms. glick said the arresting authorities didn't tell the two why they were being held
israeli officials allege that ms. glick, of north college hill, ohio, and john benvenuto, 42, of boston were carrying posters bearing the names of slain palestinians in ramallah, a west bank city. they were arrested saturday on charges of incitement
benvenuto's mother, who talked to her son by telephone sunday morning, said she was relieved that the two were unharmed during the ordeal, which lasted more than 24 hours
he said if he hadn't been an american, they would have beaten him,'' said marian benvenuto of rochester, n.y. she said her son had written to her of israelis beating palestinian protesters
mrs. benvenuto said her son told her the two were not demonstrating at the time of their arrest, though she said her son has been involved in past demonstrations against the israeli occupation of the west bank
benvenuto and ms. glick teach at a private school in of ramallah
israeli police tried to make benvenuto, an art teacher, sign a confession in hebrew that he was guilty of incitement, said mrs. benvenuto. however, she said, her son doesn't speak hebrew fluently and refused to sign
authorities didn't allow the two to consult a lawyer or american officials until early sunday, when david goode, a representative of the u.s. consulate in east jerusalem, was permitted to see them, said mrs. benvenuto. the two were released shortly afterward
the israelis have been trying to quiet three months of protest against their 20-year occupation of the west bank and gaza strip. more than 70 palestinians have been reported killed by israeli forces during that time
benvenuto and ms. glick were arrested in a street near the friends girls' school, a quaker-run facility in ramallah, mrs. benvenuto said
he was just walking down the street, he and this other teacher, going home for lunch,'' she said. ``soldiers (from the israeli army) stopped them and searched them and then turned them over to the police in ramallah
he said he and this girl each had a plastic shopping bag and inside the bag, he had pieces of cardboard with names of different palestinians who had been killed (allegedly by israeli occupation forces).''
she said she wasn't sure if the names were intended for use in a protest, but that the two were not protesting at the time
he was in different protest marches, he's been tear-gassed, and obviously they have a picture of him,'' she said. ``the american consul (goode) told me it was a warning to john to back off and mind his own business.''
mrs. benvenuto said her son believed press coverage of the arrests prompted the israelis to release the two americans early. he was initially told he would be detained for 48 hours
gold dropped 60 cents an ounce monday, opening at $431.74. it closed saturday at $432.34. members who used a0684, am-obit-oslund, sent feb. 27 under a honolulu dateline, or a0697, am-deaths, sent the same day, are asked to use the following story.</note>
the associated press incorrectly reported sunday that lula e. ``tiny'' oslund, 91, who died here thursday, was silent screen star blanche sweet
ms. sweet, who worked with filmmaker d.w. griffith, died sept. 6, 1986, in new york
mrs. oslund's son, wilman f. oslund, said sunday that he had honored a request from his mother that her obituary identify her as ms. sweet. ``in her mind, she was blanche sweet,'' said oslund, 55
oslund said his mother had always told him she was the silent screen star who played heroines for griffith in such films as ``the lonedale operator'' (1911) and ``judith of bethulia'' (1913)
oslund said he saw no harm in complying with his mother's request. he said that he believes his mother worked as a stand-in for ms. sweet and that mrs. oslund closely resembled the actress
author joseph f. clarke identified ms. sweet as daphne wayne in his 1977 book ``pseudonyms: the names behind the names.''
albania has allowed its first group of yugoslav tourists into the secluded and closely guarded eastern european nation, yugoslavia's official tanjug news agency reported sunday
the weekend trip by 130 tourists, organized by a slovenian travel company and albantours, included visits to the albanian capital of tirana as well as durres, elbasan and shkoder
the communist nation of 2.8 million has permitted very limited tourism and trips by a few foreign journalists since the late 1940s, but the nation's attendance of a meeting of balkan foreign ministers in belgrade last week was seen as the latest sign of albania's slow abandonment of isolation
at last week's meeting, foreign minister reis malile of albania became the first albanian government minister to visit neighboring yugoslavia since world war ii
the democratic presidential candidates debated the problems of the south on sunday _ minus front-runners michael dukakis and richard gephardt
it was the democrats' second debate in two days, with one more talkfest on the schedule monday
apparently, they don't care much about texas and the south,'' former colorado sen. gary hart said of the missing contenders
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. also criticized the two absent candidates at the first opportunity
maybe they didn't enjoy the debate last week in dallas,'' gore said. ``we miss them and i want them to know they're missed,'' he added
simon, who announced last week he would not campaign actively in the super tuesday states, said his presence sunday proved he was not writing off the south
i need and want and care for your votes,'' he said after the debate. he said there were no winners or losers in the debate ``with the exception'' of dukakis and gephardt
the massachusetts governor and the missouri congressman have been trading victories in the early contests. gephardt won iowa; dukakis won new hampshire. gephardt won south dakota; dukakis won minnesota. on sunday, dukakis won maine's democratic caucuses
jackson was the only candidate who did not criticize gephardt and dukakis for not coming to houston
i do not know why they chose not to be here. i do not think it reflects a lack of interest or lack of integrity. they simply made other priorities,'' he said
debate spokeswoman dee shoup said gephardt and dukakis cited scheduling conflicts
about 800 people attended the debate at the george r. brown convention center, and the forum was televised
former cbs anchorman walter cronkite hosted the debate, but he did not question the candidates. television journalist linda ellerbee was the moderator
several of the candidates described themselves as providing leadership to the rest of the field
my presence has influenced the other leaders,'' jackson said. ``you now hear gephardt saying we must challenge the multinational corporations _ that's jesse jackson. when you now hear congress saying stop the drug flow _ that's jesse jackson. when you hear other candidates talking about south africa for the first time _ that's jesse jackson.''
hart, too, said he was showing the way for the rest
i'm the only one who has put out a budget, although i see each of these people gradually creeping towards that inevitability that i think they are going to have to face
the fundamental point here is that paul talks about his programs, jesse talks about his programs, and al talks about his. i'm the only one who puts out a budget to tell americans the truth,'' he said
on another subject, gore said he supports a national energy policy that includes a price floor, incentives for domestic oil production and discouragement of oil imports
we have got to have a national energy policy,'' he said
the candidates appeared before the national association of television program executives
world merchandise trade grew more quickly last year than in 1986 and, barring economic upheavals, should expand at least as quickly this year, a report by a world trade group said monday
the crash of world stock markets last october does not appear to ``have had an immediate adverse impact'' on global commerce, said the secretariat of the general agreement on tariffs and trade
early estimates show the volume of world merchandise trade rose by 4 percent last year compared to 3.5 percent in 1986, the world trade agency's analysts said
barring a further major upheaval in financial markets or a serious recession in the united states, it should grow at least as rapidly in 1988,'' they said
last september, gatt had predicted only about 3.5 percent growth for 1987
the report expressed concern about trade imbalances among the world's largest economies. also, third world debt and protectionist pressures still burden the world economy, it said
but consumer and investor confidence has survived the stock crash better than analysts forecasted immediately after the crisis, the report said
the improvement in the outlook for trade in recent months means that, all other things being equal, the risk of a recession in 1988 is smaller,'' gatt chief economist richard blackhurst said
the value of merchandise exports rose 15.5 percent in 1987 to a new record of $2.45 billion, partly reflecting the depreciation of the u.s. dollar and higher prices for crude oil and other commodities, the report said
manufactured goods led the expansion with a 5 percent rise in volume, up from 3.5 percent in 1986. farm exports rebounded to an estimated 4 percent rise after a decline of 1 percent, the report said
reduced petroleum trade helped push trade volume in mining products down 1 percent
imports by industrialized market economies remained the strongest force in world trade expansion, though growth slowed to 5 percent from 8.5 percent in 1986, the report said
another factor cited was fast growth in asian economies such as hong kong, south korea, singapore and taiwan. these countries have become significant buyers of manufactured goods on world markets as well as exporters, gatt said
export growth in developing countries slowed to 6 percent from 9 percent in 1986, but remained more vigorous than in other parts of the world
the report noted improved trade performance by a group of 15 heavily indebted countries, including 10 in latin america
state-controlled economies like china and the soviet bloc expanded their trade less than other countries, particularly because they squeezed imports to adjust to lower export revenues from fuels and debt service requirements, the report said
the gatt includes about 100 member nations and was set up after world war ii. it is both an agreement and a forum for removing trade barriers and ensuring the free movement of goods around the world. it is administered by a permanent commission by the same name in geneva
time ran out for the u.s. athletes when the winter olympics ended sunday, with a team headed by brent rushlaw a tick away from a u.s. bobsled medal and dutch speed skater yvonne van gennip a triple gold medalist with time to spare
the best america could do was six medals, its worst winter games showing in 52 years. two of the six were gold medals, won by brian boitano in figure skating and bonnie blair in speed skating. blair also won a bronze in speed skating, making her america's only double winner
the olympics wrapped up sunday evening with a rousing closing ceremony before 60,000 people in mcmahon stadium. the 250 figure skaters who performed included past and present medal winners as well as young skaters from albertville, france, site of the 1992 winter games, and seoul, south korea, site of this year's summer games
athletes marched in carrying miniature olympic torches, and banners reading ``until we meet again'' in eight languages were draped along the top of the stands
earlier sunday, rushlaw and his three team members missed winning the first u.s. bobsled medal in 32 years when they was beaten by .02 seconds for the bronze
van gennip took more than six seconds off her own world record in the 5,000 meters to win her third gold medal. american mary docter was 22.87 seconds behind. east germans finished 2-3 in the race
finland won the hockey silver medal, handing the soviets their first loss of the games, 2-1. the soviets clinched the gold medal friday night, and america finished seventh for the second straight time
in 1936, america won just four medals, but only 51 were available then. this time, 138 medals were handed out
the soviets finished first in both number of gold medals, with 11, and total medals, with 29, a record for the winter olympics. east germany's athletes won nine golds, 25 overall; while switzerland's team came in third in both gold medals, five, and overall medals, 15
four other teams also bested the united states in terms of overall medals: austria, west germany, finland and the netherlands
bow-tied drivers in refrigerated vans are rushing prime rib and triple-layer carrot cake to upscale homes here to test the water for home-delivered gourmet meals in an industry dominated by pizza
the creation of ``the order inn,'' an experimental division of food giant general mills inc., was spurred by some compelling demographics, industry analysts say. the secretive test targets affluent singles and professional couples
what we're seeing is the beginning of an escalating delivery war, not just with pizza but with all kinds of home-delivered food,'' said charlie henderson, vice president of marketing for godfather's pizza, an omaha, neb.-based division of pillsbury inc
people are time-short and dollar-rich,'' said henderson, whose company is shrinking sit-down areas in its new restaurants and mobilizing larger road forces. ``they don't want to eat out. they're more than willing to pay to have it brought to their houses and i don't see it ending.''
the explosion of convenience food in all its frozen and home-delivered variations can be traced to two late-'80s phenomena, said stephen carnes, managing director of research for the brokerage firm of piper, jaffray &amp; hopwood
carnes said his company's research shows 65 percent of u.s. homes now have microwave ovens and 55 percent of all married women work. households typically are short on time for cooking and long on money to pay others to do it
but restaurants have shortcomings as an alternative to kitchen toil, henderson and others note. costs can be high and there's usually a wait
moreover, food industry analysts say that, in an age of vcrs, staying at home _ ``cocooning,'' as it's been dubbed _ is becoming an end in itself
grocery stores around the country have scurried to meet the demand with wider offerings of prepared and semi-prepared dinners. the choices range from macaroni and cheese on the low end to london broil and rattlesnake at the top
even a drive to the grocery store can sometimes be too strenuous for the work-weary, said peter flatow, president of the new york market research company brainreserve, inc
the goal is delivering a nice dinner to them; the challenge is overcoming high cost and logistics
domino's pizza has done it. now all you've got to do is get veal marsala there and you've got it,'' flatow said. ``the need is there. nobody has fulfilled it yet.''
a general mills spokesman would not discuss the order inn venture, citing competitive factors. local analysts say it has been under way for roughly six months
industry watchers describe it as a logical step for general mills, which also owns the red lobster, york's and olive garden restaurant chains. based in golden valley, a minneapolis suburb, the company also has takeout experience. it recently sold its chain of leann chin's chinese restaurants, which offered both sit-down and eat-at-home meals
order inn menus being dropped off at twin cities homes in recent months promise free delivery, usually in less than 20 minutes. both lunches and dinners are available, seven days a week
the menu offers four selections in the appetizers and salad section, including chilled shrimp and popcorn chicken. two sandwiches are available and five entrees, ranging from $5.75 for lasagna to $10.95 for prime rib. white-chocolate macadamia nut cheesecake highlights the three dessert choices
the menus include detailed instructions on reheating in a microwave or oven,. and a questionnaire asking what was ordered and how the food and service ranked
no verdict is in sight on the order inn, but experts say general mills seems to have the right idea
i don't think there's any question there will be more to follow,'' said craig carver, senior vice president of the minneapolis brokerage firm of dain bosworth
a chief obstacle to success is keeping costs under control. with pizza, for example, gasoline, drivers, insurance and other costs take a $3 to $4 slice out of a $10 pizza, godfather's henderson says
an extra hurdle for order inn is the daily gamble on how many orders will be placed for each item. leftovers must be disposed of at day's end, general mills spokesman craig shulstad confirmed
whatever the future of the experiment, industry watchers predict scratch cooking will become ever more a recreational, weekend pastime. and restaurants, they say, should beware
it's really a fight for share of stomach,'' carver said
angolan rebels claimed they killed 172 government soldiers and captured three soviet-built tanks in recent fighting, the independent south african press association reported sunday
the guerrillas destroyed three angolan military units friday in a battle east of cuito cuanavale in southeastern angola, the news agency reported. it cited a statement released at rebel headquarters in jamba
unita, the national union for the total independence of angola, also claimed its guerrillas killed 10 cuban soldiers and destroyed seven soviet-made t-55 tanks, the report said
the statement said five rebels were killed and four were wounded in friday's battles
both angola's marxist government and the u.s.-  and south african-supported rebels have reported heavy fighting around cuito cuanavale in recent weeks
unita said in january that it forced government troops to flee cuito cuanavale and guerrilla forces encircled the vacated town. unita leader jonas savimbi has been predicting his rebels would defeat the remaining government in the area and then move into cuito cuanavale
the town was used as a government base in annual dry-season offensives against unita strongholds in the southeast
angola gained its independence from portugal in novermber 1975, and unita lost to the marxist forces in the civil war that followed. government forces are backed by some 40,000 cuban troops and more than 1,000 soviet military advisers
also sunday, south africa announced that two of its soldiers were killed in angola. the military statement said the troops were slain thursday by ``indirect enemy fire.''
south africa announced in november that it had intervened militarily in southern angola on behalf of unita. a month later south africa said it had begun to withdraw its troops, but it remains engaged in the fighting
south africa has announced the deaths of more than 30 south african military personnel since november, but has not disclosed the extent of its involvement. angola claims 9,000 south african troopers are in angola
a taiwanese dissident arrested trying to board a flight to taiwan with a false passport said monday he agreed to leave the philippines and would depart for the united states
hsu hsin-liang said he would leave monday aboard a korean air flight for seoul, south korea, and would travel on to hawaii
hsu, who edits the taiwan times newspaper in los angeles, was banned from taiwan in 1979 for political activity
immigration officials said hsu agreed to self-deportation, meaning he would be free to return to the philippines. philippine authorities had offered to accept him as a political refugee but he declined, saying he wanted to return to taiwan
hsu was arrested feb. 11 while preparing to board a flight for the taiwanese capital of taipei
taiwanese officials refused to allow him to return to taiwan because people charged with sedition are not allowed to enter the country under the national security law, which replaced martial rule last july
taiwan had been under martial law since 1949, when the nationalist chinese lost a mainland civil war with the communists, fled to the island and established a government
hsu was charged with sedition for his alleged involvement in an anti-government riot in taiwan's southern port of kaohsiung in 1979. the riot occurred two months after hsu had left for the united states, but taiwanese officials said he helped organize it
in september 1986, hsu organized a u.s.-based taiwanese group, the democratic progressive party overseas that is affiliated with taiwan's opposition democratic progressive party. not hold caucuses. they are counted below as reporting, but their vote totals are counted as zero.</note>
