madonna's divorce plans were created by the press, says her husband, sean penn, who vowed in an interview published sunday to ``refocus'' himself to avoid outbursts like the one that landed him in jail
penn, filmdom's bad boy, discussed the strain of being married to the darling of american pop in a chicago tribune interview billed as the first since he was jailed for 32 days last summer after striking a movie extra
i feel uncomfortable commenting about my family situation because i'm no expert on the subject. obviously making any family work is an endless job that's hard enough even when the family isn't public,'' penn said
madonna filed divorce papers in santa monica, calif., on dec. 4, citing irreconcilable differences. two weeks later, she asked to withdraw the petition and the court granted the request the same day, court records show. no reason was given in the court papers for her change of heart
but penn, 27, said nevertheless that talk about the possibility of divorce ``was more people magazine than reality. my attitude with the press right now is that i hope they've had their share of me. they've been very busy trying to find or make dirt. i'd like to get back to acting.''
penn said his reported marital problems with madonna, 29, stem from her fans' view of him as less-than-ideal marriage material
the couple were married aug. 16, 1985, in a lavish ceremony on a malibu, calif., bluff overlooking the pacific ocean, while news helicopters buzzed overhead
she belonged to them, to the public,'' penn said. ``and if anybody took her, i think they thought it should have been someone more acceptable, like donald trump
the public is very possessive about rock stars,'' penn said, ``and about her in particular. they don't want to share their love.''
penn may not be able to shed his reputation, but he said he plans to try to avoid future confrontations
certainly i've thought about it,'' he said. ``i just have to refocus myself in another direction.''
of his california jail experience, penn said he was never afraid
i was in a jail with all the big shots, one person to a cell _ solitary confinement for 24 hours. so afraid, no. but bored, yes. after about two weeks of that kind of boredom, i think i would have preferred some fear.''
penn spoke with the tribune after dinner. he had fettuccine with shrimp. madonna ``had a caesar salad,'' he said. ``she always has caesar salads.''
the body of a 23-year-old northern ireland man fatally shot at a british army checkpoint was exhumed sunday for another autopsy in ireland
aidan mcanespie's family requested the new autopsy. they said he had been harassed at the border and disputed the army statement that the bullet that struck him while he was near the border checkpoint at aughnacloy, in northren ireland, on feb. 21 was fired accidentally and ricocheted
an 18-year-old soldier has been charged with unlawful killing in the death and is being held on bail in military care
the british and irish governments are conducting separate investigations
mcanespie's body was buried tuesday in clara, county monaghan, in the irish republic across the border from aughnacloy following an autopsy by british medical examiners
prime minister charles haughey of ireland on saturday approved the exhumation after receiving a request from the family
an overnight police guard was placed at the cordoned-off grave, and after the exhumation the coffin was transferred to monaghan general hospital for the autopsy
the dead man's sister, eilish mccabe, claimed sunday that her brother had received a number of death threats from british soldiers
she said in an an irish radio interview that her brother received ``continuous harassment'' during border crossings from his northern ireland home to his job in the irish republic
haughey is to make a statement on the incident to the dail, ireland's parliament, tuesday
northern ireland is a british province. guerrillas of the mainly roman catholic irish republican army have been fighting since 1969 to unite the province, where protestants outnumber catholics 3-2, with the predominantly catholic irish republic
eds: leads with 5 grafs, bush claims victory, picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng: the maine caucuses
george bush, claiming a solid victory sunday in maine's republican presidential caucuses, was attacked by chief rival bob dole on the iran-contra affair, while rep. jack kemp blasted the two gop frontrunners on taxes
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won the maine democratic caucuses, scoring another victory on his new england home turf, and jesse jackson scored a surprisingly strong second, followed by an uncommitted bloc
today our message continued to shine,'' the massachusetts governor said in a statement. ``today's victory gives our national campaign another push toward success on super tuesday.''
the state republican party provided no official count, but various campaigns agreed bush, who makes his summer home in maine, was far ahead, with former television evangelist pat robertson next, followed by the uncommitteds
i am delighted with what appears to be an overwhelming victory in the maine caucuses, assuring my campaign of all 22 national delegates,'' bush said from washington
the maine caucuses pick delegates to the parties' state conventions this spring, where national convention delegates are chosen
four of the six democrats, meanwhile, gathered for a debate in houston, where the absentees _ dukakis and rep. richard gephardt _ came under fire for skipping the event
at a republican debate in atlanta _ the first full-scale gop face-off of the southern campaign _ dole took aim at bush for the reagan administration's decision to trade arms for hostages in the iran-contra affair. that, he said, was a big mistake
we never should trade arms for hostages. we shouldn't issue these reports and say we shouldn't trade arms for hostages _ the vice president's report _ and then later go to a meeting and say it's all right. we shouldn't do those things,'' dole said, holding up a report on terrorism that was written by a presidential commission headed by bush
bush did not respond directly, but did say ``mistakes were made'' in the iran-contra affair
kemp, whose campaign has been faltering after poor showings in early contests, accused bush and dole of supporting tax hikes
they sound alike. they talk alike. they've supported every single tax increase over the last eight years,'' the new york congressman said. ``if they're nominated, the reagan revolution is over, gone, dead.''
dole hit back, saying: ``jack's never met a deficit he didn't like.'' and bush told the new york congressman: `you don't care about deficits. you never have, and they're public enemy no. 1.''
bush is planning to skip the league of women voters' debate next sunday in nashville, his campaign manager said
at this time, there are no debates on the schedule,'' lee atwater told reporters after the atlanta debate. ``we're simply at a point where we've got 20 states; you've got to maintain control of your schedule.''
the gop contest was sponsored by the atlanta journal-constitution newspapers, which also organized a democratic face-off on saturday. there, dukakis made stinging attacks on rivals gephardt and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee
gore, who largely bypassed early contests in new hampshire and iowa, is pinning his hopes on a strong showing on super tuesday, march 8. on that day, 20 states, mostly in the south, will hold primaries or caucuses
sen. sam nunn of georgia, who disappointed many democrats when he decided to sit out the presidential race, said sunday he still hasn't decided whether to lend his backing to his fellow southerner
i like al gore,'' nunn said in an interview on nbc-tv's ``meet the press.'' ``i like what he says on national security.''
but, he said, ``i also like dick gephardt. ... i'm not ducking it. i just haven't decided who i'm going to vote for yet. i like gore and i like gephardt.''
gephardt and dukakis, responsible for the sharpest sparring among the democrats lately, did not attend sunday night's democratic debate in houston. gary hart attacked the absentees
apparently they don't care much about texas and the south,'' the former colorado senator said. those who did attend the debate, however, admitted they're getting a bit tired of such gatherings
we really are kind of trapped in these 90-second sound bites trying to say a thing that makes a difference,'' said jackson
there really is a problem in these debates, in that we have to answere in 60 seconds, or 90 seconds, and in some debates 30 seconds,'' said paul simon
dukakis campaigned sunday from the deck of a fire boat in baltimore's harbor, and pledged to make affordable housing a priority if elected. maryland is one of the states voting on super tuesday
jackson, in tampa, fla., visited a crime-ridden neighborhood and decried the despair and frustration that has led to clashes between residents and police
jackson has pledged to raise the minimum wage, provide long-term health insurance for all americans and to make fighting drugs his top priority
the sandinistas are not threatening the streets of tampa this morning,'' he said. ``the no. 1 threat is coke, crack and heroin.''
in another development, a poll published sunday suggested dukakis and gephardt have the lead among democrats in texas, the biggest super tuesday state. on the republican side, bush had a clear lead, with dole a distant second
the poll was conducted for the houston chronicle and the dallas morning news
among 301 likely democratic primary voters surveyed, dukakis had 22 percent; gephardt 21 percent; jackson 12 percent; gore, 10 percent; hart, 8 percent; and simon 1 percent
among republicans, bush had the support of 60 percent of the 298 likely republican primary voters surveyed. dole had 14 percent; robertson 8 percent; and kemp 3 percent. fourteen percent were undecided
the poll's margin of error is plus or minus 6 percentage points. it was conducted by university of houston political scientist richard murray through the university's center for public policy. news digest: panama city _ panama; wash _ oas-panama; jerusalem _ shultz; abud, occupied west bank _ israel; lod, israel _ military courts; nicosia, cyprus _ iran-iraq; wash _ summit; undated _ political rdp; atlanta _ republican debate; hinesburg, vt. _ home burial.</note>
the united states, its u.n. prestige and influence already at an all-time low, faces a showdown monday when the general assembly convenes an emergency session to condemn u.s. efforts to close the plo mission
some arab leaders say they want to shift the next general assembly meeting to geneva to punish the united states for harassing the palestine liberation organization, which the united nations recognizes
the entire u.n. operation here, including the general assembly, funnels $400 million to $700 million year into the u.s. and new york economies, according to the u.s. mission
mikhail s. gorbachev met with two prominent armenian writers in an unusual personal campaign to allay concerns of armenians demanding annexation of land in a neighboring republic, two activists said sunday
the writers, silva kaputikyan and zori balayan, met with the soviet leader on friday, said sergei grigoryants, a moscow-based dissident, and hovik vassilian, an armenian activist and editor of the underground journal, the armenian matter
they said the writers met thursday with politburo member and propaganda chief alexander n. yakovlev
when the arizona senate opens gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial monday, it will embark on a course laid out in england as a way to remove cruel kings and brought to america in colonial days as a way to protect democracy
but despite the long and sometimes colorful history of impeachment, legal scholars say the seldom-used laws are ill defined. arizona lawmakers grappling with mecham's fate have to make up many rules as they go along
the arizona constitution provides few standards or procedures for how the senate is to perform its role,'' said university of arizona law professor robert glennon
chrysler corp.'s plans to close a wisconsin assembly plant and its admission that it might sell its acustar inc. parts subsidiary are fueling worker anger and distrust as the two sides head into this summer's national contract talks
chrysler's parts operations were grouped into the subsidiary last spring, but most of acustar's 28,000 workers have been with chrysler since it battled back from the brink of bankruptcy early in the decade, when they granted concessions to keep the company afloat
chrysler workers think the potential sale, now that the no. 3 carmaker is again earning billion-dollar profits, indicates they won't be able to trust the company in the upcoming contract negotiations
it has been 10 months since the trial began, seven months since the first witness appeared and an incredible five years since the mcmartin pre-school molestation case hit the courts
and there is no end in sight
prosecutors say they will conclude their presentation by july, but the defense isn't saying how long it may take
for nine months, the justice department has given the impression attorney general edwin meese removed himself from the pollard spy case. but now it acknowledges he was briefed twice about the case and it says he never was excluded
in what chief department spokesman terry eastland called a correction, he said meese is only excluded from the espionage case against the israeli air force officer who recruited navy counterterrorism analyst jonathan pollard as a spy
meese is free to be briefed and even to make decisions in the still-open pollard case to the extent that they don't involve the case against israeli brig. gen. aviem sella, eastland said
presidential candidates from congress work in a system where it's hard to avoid some flip-flopping on issues but when a candidate can't offer convincing explanations, those charges take root with voters, experts say
two democratic candidates battling for super tuesday votes, missouri rep. richard gephardt and tennessee sen. albert gore, have been the most frequent targets, even trading those accusations themselves. both, as legislators, have voted on two sides of several issues
gephardt has taken fire for moving to the left after deciding to run for president, on abortion, trade and social issues. gore has become more conservative, especially on defense matters
rep. richard gephardt moves into super tuesday territory with an extraordinarily effective television advertising campaign that touched raw nerves and won last-minute support among voters in earlier democratic presidential contests
while critics complain that gephardt's populist image is an insider's affectation and his hard-hitting ``hyundai'' trade ad is based on bad numbers, there's little disagreement about the impact of the missouri congressman's tv campaign
the forceful spots, created by political veterans david doak and robert shrum, are credited with putting gephardt over the top in iowa and south dakota and enabling him to stop a new hampshire slide that could have jostled him out of the second place finish he needed and got
congress faces a confusing choice this week between two rival versions of a plan to help the nicaraguan rebels
a vote is scheduled for thursday to decide whether the u.s.-backed contras will get an aid package drafted by house democrats, a similar one drawn up by house republicans, or nothing at all
current authority to aid the contras expires at midnight monday, and the rebels are said to be rapidly running out of items like food, clothing and medicine that the new aid plans would provide
the fertile missouri river bottom lands where the arikara, hidatsa and mandan indians thrived for seven centuries are gone forever, buried beneath the waters of lake sakakawea
the 200-mile-long reservoir drove the indians onto higher, less productive land, sliced their reservation into isolated sections and is blamed for precipitating soaring unemployment and alcoholism
the three tribes, who say they were coerced into surrendering the bottom lands without just compensation as the lake filled behind garrison dam, believe they have a chance this year to get $178.4 million that they and a special federal commission think they deserve
enrollment is up and the debt is down at fisk university, where only a few years ago students shivered in unheated dormitories because the historically black private institution could not pay its gas bill
as fisk winds down its celebration of black history month, which included the dedication of a stamp honoring author james weldon johnson, faculty and students also celebrated the university's return from the brink of financial disaster
when the nashville gas co. cut off service in early 1984 until fisk paid a $170,000 debt, students brought space heaters to class and joined with faculty and staff members to raise funds to ensure the university's survival. the overall debt mounted to $4.1 million, but classes continued
cream pies flew, old flicks rolled and fans talked to to an old three stooges supporting actor when about 1,000 die-hard fans of the celebrated knuckleheads gathered for a weekend of _ nyuk, nyuk _ stoogemania
i've loved larry, moe and curly ever since i was 5 years old,'' said virginia riviera, 30, who came with two friends from salem, mass
they and others swapped memorabilia, threw pies and watched such films as ``three little pigskins,'' ``all the world's a stooge,'' ``dizzy doctors'' and ``disorder in the court.''
does anyone pay attention to a 6-foot-7 kibbitzer who used to be the second most powerful man in washington?
paul volcker is beginning to find out
the former chairman of the federal reserve recently broke a self-imposed vow of silence to resume offering opinions on deficits, taxes and the health of the economy
he seemed to show a little of the old magical influence last thursday when stock and bond prices sank soon after he called for a tax increase and predicted that interest rates would rise
but some skeptics said the markets' behavior had nothing to do with what volcker said
he's not even associated with the fed anymore,'' said hildegarde zagorski, a market strategist at prudential-bache securities inc
when you get a day like (thursday), everybody tries to say what killed the market and they drag out every news item that would have passed unnoticed,'' she said
so is volcker capable of moving the market? ``no. not at all,'' ms. zagorski said
volcker still has not settled down to a new job since his departure from the federal reserve last august, when he was succeeded by alan greenspan. but volcker is expected to announce his career decision within the next few weeks
meanwhile, he is borrowing an office on wall street and heading a washington-based commission on how to improve the quality of the nation's civil service
speaking on the lecture circuit helps pay the bills and gives volcker a forum to express his views on the need to cut the federal budget deficit
the forum for his remarks thursday was a luncheon meeting in san antonio of the national association of industrial and office parks
the night before, volcker had spoken in peoria, ill., at the washington day banquet of the creve coeur club
in peoria, volcker was chosen as a contrast to the 1987 speaker, bob hope
we certainly know it's difficult to upstage a bob hope, so we said let's go back to something that's not comparable,'' said henry allovio, the club's vice president
according to those who believe in volcker's continuing influence, his remarks in san antonio triggered a selloff in the bond market, which scared owners of stock-index futures, which in turn dragged down stock prices
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, which had been up as much as 33 points, ended up with a loss for the day of 22.38 points, most of it in the final hour of trading
i have deep respect for paul volcker and in my opinion there is not a single more influential economist in this country,'' said john v. sebastian, executive vice president and chief economist of clayton brown &amp; associates in chicago
but can volcker influence trading decisions even without the control over the nation's money supply that he once had? yes, sebastian said
as an example, he mentioned henry kaufman, a prominent economist for the giant wall street investment firm salomon brothers inc. whose outlooks used to move interest rates in the bond market. in december kaufman announced plans to start his own consulting firm
henry kaufman in his heyday had no authority and yet he was able to influence the markets,'' sebastian said
more than 5,000 automotive engineers will meet this week to talk about everything concerning the life of a vehicle, from computerized conception to disposal on the junk heap
the society for automotive engineers 1988 congress and exposition also will be attended by more than 700 industry suppliers, who will display their latest developments in automotive plastics and other materials, lubricants, design systems and maintenance. they'll occupty 167,000 square feet of exhibit space at detroit's downtown cobo hall from monday through thursday
the convention's theme is ``engineering for the '90s _ imagination, innovation.'' among featured speakers will be general motors corp. president robert stempel and anthony rudd, deputy chairman of lotus engineering
special sessions include a panel's look at the growing problem of disposing of automotive plastics as their use expands internally, in the engine and passenger compartment, and externally, as more and more body parts are composed of stronger, reinforced plastic substances
the engineers also will discuss efforts to reduce release of ozone-depleting chloroflourocarbons, or cfcs, used in production. automaking has been the main source of cfc emissions since the united states ended cfc use in aerosol sprays in the 1970s
ford motor co. vice chairman harold poling will be honored monday at a luncheon hosted by automotive industries magazine, which named him its man of the year for 1988. the trade magazine noted poling's stabilizing, corporate-wide strategy of cost-cutting and balanced production while focusing on quality and cooperation with workers, dealers and suppliers
the strategy has allowed ford to run factories at profitable levels, introduce attractive innovations and eliminate most plant closures, the magazine reported in a cover story on poling
as a result, ford outearned gm, the much larger industry leader, in 1986 and 1987 and is expected to remain the biggest money-maker in the industry in 1988, while gm is still fighting to cut costs and balance a huge modernization and new products program
described as the largest vehicle engineering conference, the gathering will include engineers from ford, gm, chrysler corp., toyota motor corp., honda motor co. as well as hundreds of suppliers including allied automotive, borg-warner, dupont automotive, general electric, united technologies and dow chemical
irving bank corp., target of a $1.08 billion hostile takeover proposal by bank of new york that was sanctioned last week by government regulators, said sunday it would brief shareholders on why they should reject the bid and predicted a bitterly fought battle for their votes
irving plans to bring to the attention of its shareholders all the factors they should consider regarding the offer, as well as questioning exactly how bank of new york intends to meet the numerous conditions to which its offer is now subject,'' the bank said in a press statement
it was irving's first official reaction to the approval given last thursday by the federal reserve board and new york state banking board bank of the bank of new york's hostile $60 a share bid in cash and securities
the takeover fight has attracted attention because hostile acquisitions are unusual in the normally staid banking world. some analysts have said government approval portends hostile takeovers of other banks
fed and state officials dismissed the unfriendly nature of the bid as irrelevant and said they saw no competitive threat to a merger of the two new york banks, which would create the nation's 12th largest banking company with assets of nearly $42 billion
nevertheless, the fed imposed one important condition of approval by requiring bank of new york to sell additional stock to replenish the $264 million cash portion of the takeover. in addition, the fed said at least 60 percent of that amount must be raised before the transaction can be completed
although bank of new york officials expressed confidence they could meet the condition, irving called it significant hurdles because it will dilute the stock's value and must be approved by bank of new york shareholders
the bank of new york's offer depends on receipt of two-thirds of irving's shares. the offer could encounter more difficulty because of a new york law that impedes hostile takeovers
irving said the fed's approval ``clearly opens the way for a bitterly fought proxy battle.''
proxies are written statements authorizing others to vote stock on the behalf of shareholders, a normal arrangement in publicly held companies. management routinely solicits shareholder proxies but they are also used by others attempting to win control away from management
the fed's approval does not change the nature of the proposal, which continues to make no business sense and is not in the best long-term interest of irving,'' said the irving statement
it said the bank ``is fully committed to continue opposing this grossly inadequate and highly conditional proposal, which the corporation's unanimous board is convinced is not in irving's best interests.''
